                 = 2348\n Female                         = 2441\n Total Households               = 862\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|28.74|82.32|type:adm2nd_region:NP_source:unmaps-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              = +977-88 \n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = [http://www.ddcrukum.gov.np www.ddcrukum.gov.np]\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Ghetma ''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Rukum District]] in the [[Rapti Zone]] of western [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[2011 National Population and Housing Census]] it had a population of 4789 people in which 2348 male and 2441 female are living in 862 individual households.Here is a Higher Secondary School named Shree Adarsh Higher Secondary School Ghetma, Rukum which was established in 2030 B.S. as primary school and then upgraded as High School in 2057 B.S. at the same way it made Higher Secondary School in 2067 B.S. Each wards of it has primary Schools including 3 lower secondary Schools. It is located in bank of Thuli Bheri River from Bhalma to Rimna named places. Here is a locally famous cave named Saattale Guffa located in jungle of ward No.1. In past it was a part of Aathbis DandaGaun VDC which used to occupy 2 wards of it. Formerly it departed from that as one of small VDC in south-west area of Rukum district with the area of only around 29 km<sup>2</sup>.\n\n==References==\nUpdated by Puskar Malla with the help of report of National Population and Housing Census 2011 (Population)\n\n{{Western Rukum District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Western Rukum District]]\n\n\n{{Karnali-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Ghetma\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0918\u0947\u0924\u092e\u093e \n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  = Nativeland and our Parents are Greater than Heaven\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             =\n|image_seal             =\n|image_map              = <!-- NepalRukumDistrictmap.png -->\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Map of the village development committees in Rukum District\n|pushpin_map            = Nepal\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Nepal\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Zones of Nepal|Zone]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Rapti Zone]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Rukum District]]\n|<!-- Politics -->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    --> \n|unit_pref                =  <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   -->\n|population_as_of               = 2011\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 4789\n Male                           = 2348\n Female                         = 2441\n Total Households               = 862\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|28.74|82.32|type:adm2nd_region:NP_source:unmaps-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              = +977-88 \n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = [http://www.ddcrukum.gov.np www.ddcrukum.gov.np]\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Ghetma ''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Rukum District]] in the [[Rapti Zone]] of western [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[2011 National Population and Housing Census]] it had a population of 4789 people in which 2348 male and 2441 female are living in 862 individual households.Here is a Higher Secondary School named Shree Adarsh Higher Secondary School Ghetma, Rukum which was established in 2030 B.S. as primary school and then upgraded as High School in 2057 B.S. at the same way it made Higher Secondary School in 2067 B.S. Each wards of it has primary Schools including 3 lower secondary Schools. It is located in bank of Thuli Bheri River from Bhalma to Rimna named places. Here is a locally famous cave named Saattale Guffa located in jungle of ward No.1. In past it was a part of Aathbis DandaGaun VDC which used to occupy 2 wards of it. Formerly it departed from that as one of small VDC in south-west area of Rukum district with the area of only around 29 km<sup>2</sup>.<ref>{{Updated by Puskar Malla with the help of report of National Population and Housing Census 2011(Population) }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Rukum District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Rukum District]]\n\n\nUpdated by Puskar Malla with the help of report of National Population and Housing Census 2011(Population)\n\n\n{{Karnali-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pegship", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat, corr ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghetma"}
{"title_page": "Lakeshore East line", "text_new": "{{Infobox rail line\n | box_width   = 300px\n | name        = Lakeshore East\n | color       = ee3124\n | logo        = {{rint|gotransit|rail|B|x|size=35}}\n | logo_width  =\n | logo_alt    =\n | image       = GO 558 Pulling East from Guildwood.jpg\n | image_width = 300px\n | image_alt   =\n | caption     = GO Train approaches a level crossing at Galloway Road in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n | type        = [[Commuter rail]]\n | system      = [[GO Transit#Rail|GO Train]]\n | status      = \n | locale      = [[Toronto]]; [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering]]; [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]]; [[Whitby, Ontario|Whitby]];<br>[[Oshawa]]\n | start       =\n | end         =\n | stations    = 10\n | routes      =\n | daily_ridership = 52,000 (2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/docs/pdf/board_agenda/20140905/20140905_BoardMtg_Regional_Express_Rail_EN.pdf |title=Regional  Express Rail |date=5 September 2014 |publisher=[[Metrolinx]] |accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref>\n | open        = {{Start date|1967|05|23}}\n | close       =\n | owner       = [[Metrolinx]]\n | operator    = [[GO Transit]]\n | character   =\n | depot       =\n | stock       =\n | linelength_km = 50.5\n | tracklength = \n | tracks = \n | gauge       = {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}}\n | old_gauge =\n | minradius   =\n | racksystem  =\n | routenumber =\n | electrification =\n | speed       = \n | elevation   =\n | website     =\n | map         = {{GO Transit Lakeshore East}}\n | map_state   = \n}}\n'''Lakeshore East''' is one of the seven [[commuter rail]] lines of the [[GO Transit]] system in the [[Greater Toronto Area]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. It extends from [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] in [[Toronto]] to {{STN|Oshawa GO}} in [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]]. Buses from Oshawa connect to communities further east in [[Newcastle, Ontario|Newcastle]], [[Bowmanville, Ontario|Bowmanville]] and [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]].\n\nMost off-peak and some peak trains are interlined with the [[Lakeshore West line]], continuing to [[Aldershot GO Station|Aldershot]] or [[Niagara Falls station (Ontario)|Niagara Falls]].\n\n==History==\nThe Lakeshore East line is the second oldest of GO's services, opening as part of the then-unified Lakeshore line on GO's first day of operations, 23 May 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/May2007/23/c3558.html|title=GO celebrates 40 years of success|website=www.newswire.ca}}</ref> It is ten minutes younger than its twin; although the first train from [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering]] bound for Toronto left at 5:00 am that day, a 4:50 am departure from [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]] on Lakeshore West beat it into the record books.\n\nThe line initially ran along the [[CN Kingston Subdivision]] from Union to Pickering. Just prior to the opening of GO service, CN had moved much of its freight operations from downtown areas to the new [[MacMillan Yard]] north of the city. To feed freight traffic from the east into the Yard, CN built the new [[CN York Subdivision|York Subdivision]] across the top of the city (in what was then farmland) and connected the Yard to the Kingston Sub just west of Pickering at Pickering Junction. This offloaded the majority of traffic from the Kingston Sub between Pickering Junction and Union, allowing ample scheduling room for GO service. Sections of the Kingston Sub to the east of Pickering Junction remained in use as the mainline to [[Montreal]], and CN did not have capacity to allow GO traffic on these sections.\n\nGO had originally planned to address this as part of a much larger project known as [[GO-Urban]], and later, [[GO ALRT]]. GO ALRT would have used a new electric train car running on a dedicated right-of-way between Pickering and its terminus to the east of Harmony Road on the far eastern edge of [[Oshawa]]. ALRT was to have followed the CN lines east to Whitby, then across the 401 to follow the [[Canadian Pacific Railway|CP]] [[CP Belleville Subdivision|Belleville Sub]], which runs in parallel on the north side of the 401. Stations would be built at Pickering, Ajax, Whitby, Hopkins (west edge of Oshawa), Simcoe (downtown Oshawa), Oshawa east (at Stevenson) and finally Harmony. First proposed in 1982, ALRT lived for only a short time before it was cancelled in 1985 with a change of government.\n\nInstead, the basic alignment planned for ALRT from Pickering to Oshawa was laid using conventional track, splitting off at Pickering Junction and running under the York Sub bridge over the 401 in a complex basket weave. It ran along the original ALRT layout to Whitby, but abandoned the 401 overpass and instead continued along the CN lines to the current [[Oshawa GO Station]] on the far western edge of town. The new lines were laid in sections, reaching Oshawa in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gotransitmotive.bravehost.com/RosterStats/significantdates.htm |title=Significant dates in GO Transit |access-date=2018-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195027/http://gotransitmotive.bravehost.com/RosterStats/significantdates.htm |archive-date=2016-03-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Until 29 December 2006, weekend and holiday trains still ended in Pickering,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transit.toronto.on.ca/regional/2101.shtml |title=GO Transit's Lakeshore Line|website=Transit Toronto|author1=Daniel Garcia|author2=James Bow|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref> but service is now offered along the entire route every day of the year.\n\nIn December 1993, GO Transit initiated a program for the eastward expansion of the Lakeshore East line, for which it received approval in 1994.<ref name=\"Cole\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oshawaexpress.ca/viewposting.php?view=411|title=GO Train expansion - Will all be 'all aboard?'|last=Cole|first=Lindsay|newspaper=The Oshawa Express|date=|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> GO Transit undertook a study to determine whether to use the tracks of [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] or [[Canadian National Railway]].<ref name=\"Cole\" />\n\nMetrolinx purchased the Kingston Sub between Pickering Junction and Union on 31 March 2011.<ref name=\"CNtoGO\">{{cite news|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110330/go-metrolinx-pickering-toronto-canadian-national-railway-110330/20110330?hub=TorontoNewHome|title=GO owner buys rail line between T.O. and Pickering|publisher=CTV Toronto (CTVGlobeMedia) |date=30 March 2011|accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref> This means that GO now completely owns the Lakeshore East, Newmarket/Barrie and Stouffville corridors.\n\nOn 29 June 2013, off-peak service was improved to every 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/04/19/go_trains_to_run_every_30_minutes_all_day_on_lakeshore_lines.html|title=GO trains to run every 30 minutes all day on Lakeshore lines|last=Kalinowski|first=Tess|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers|date=19 April 2013|accessdate=2013-04-19}}</ref>  On 24 September 2018, weekday mid-day service frequency was improved again, now operating every 15 minutes.  <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/go-trains-lakeshore-service-increase-1.4831511|title=GO trains on Lakeshore lines to run more often|last=|first=|newspaper=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=20 September 2018|accessdate=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n==Service==\nAs of September 2018, local service operates every 15 minutes on weekdays mid-day, and every 30 minutes during other periods.  In addition to local service, there are up to 4 express trains per hour during weekday peak periods.<ref name=2018Schedule>{{cite web |url=https://www.gotransit.com/static_files/gotransit/assets/pdf/TripPlanning/FullSchedules/FS11012020/Table09.pdf |title=Lakeshore East Line 2020 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=11 January 2020 |website= |publisher=GO Transit |access-date=20 January 2020 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Station list==\n\nMost off-peak trains, as well as some peak trains, continue on to the Lakeshore West corridor after stopping at Union; there is no need to change trains to continue on to destinations on the Lakeshore West line.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Station\n!colspan=2|Municipality\n! Connections\n! Notes\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Bowmanville}}''\n|rowspan=8|[[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Clarington]]\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Darlington}}''\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Oshawa Central}}''\n|rowspan=3|[[Oshawa]]\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Thornton's Corners}}''\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! {{GOs|Oshawa}}\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|rail}} {{rint|ca|via}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Whitby}}\n| [[Whitby, Ontario|Whitby]]\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Ajax}}\n| [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]]\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Pickering}}\n| [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering]]\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Rouge Hill}}\n|colspan=2 rowspan=7|[[Toronto]]\n| {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]], [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Guildwood}}\n| {{rint|rail}} {{rint|ca|via}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Eglinton}}\n| {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Scarborough}}\n| {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Danforth}}\n| {{rint|toronto|subway|2}}<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar}} {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! ''East Harbour''\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union]]\n|  {{rint|gotransit|rail|A}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|C|x}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|D|x}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|F|x}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|E|x}}  {{rint|gotransit|rail|G|x}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|rail}} {{rint|us|amtrak}} {{rint|toronto|up}} {{rint|ca|via}} <br> {{rint|toronto|subway|1}}<br> {{rint|toronto|streetcar}} {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]] \n|Through service to Lakeshore West line\n|}\n\n==Expansion==\nIn 2008, Metrolinx published its regional transportation entitled ''[[The Big Move]]''. As part of this, the agency identified an express all-day service between Hamilton and Oshawa (via Toronto Union) as one of its top 15 priorities.<ref>[http://www.metrolinx.com/thebigmove/lookingforward/5_2_first15years.html The Big Move] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618135517/http://www.metrolinx.com/thebigmove/lookingforward/5_2_first15years.html |date=2010-06-18 }}, Section 5.2: The first 15 years. Retrieved July 23, 2010</ref> Metrolinx has also committed to eventually providing service every 15 minutes on the line, as well as electrifying railways. This project, dubbed [[GO Regional Express Rail|Regional Express Rail]], is expected to reduce some trip times by 20%.<ref name=\"RER LW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/regionalplanning/rer/rer_lsw.aspx|title=Metrolinx Regional Express Rail \u2013 Lakeshore West GO line|website=www.metrolinx.com}}</ref><ref name=TheStar-2015-04-17>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/transportation/2015/04/17/go-to-add-30-per-cent-more-trains-in-next-5-years-s.html |title=GO to add almost 50 per cent more trains in next 5 years |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |author=Tess Kalinowski, Transportation reporter |date={{date|2015-04-17}} |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref>\nContinued growth of the Oshawa area has led to renewed calls for expansion of the Lakeshore East line, this time all the way to [[Bowmanville, Ontario|Bowmanville]]. Possible station stops have been identified near Stevenson Road, Bloor Street, Courtice Road, and two locations in Bowmanville. There were plans to convert a building that used to be a [[Knob Hill Farms]] grocery store into a GO train station located near Simcoe Street, but the plans to build a station there have been scrapped due to environmental concerns and the challenge of reaching a fair purchase price with the property owner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1243892--metrolinx-derails-plans-for-oshawa-go-station|title=Metrolinx derails plans for Oshawa GO station |date=November 14, 2011|website=DurhamRegion.com |first=Jillian|last=Follert|archive-date=May 23, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523195140/http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1243892--metrolinx-derails-plans-for-oshawa-go-station}}</ref> However, negotiations for a station in downtown Oshawa could be reconsidered if both sides could come to an agreement on a fair purchase price for the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1246482--metrolinx-would-resume-go-negotiations-on-knob-hill-farms-site-for-the-right-price|title=Metrolinx would resume GO negotiations on Knob Hill Farms site for the right price |date=November 18, 2011|first=Jillian|last=Follert|website=DurhamRegion.com |archive-date=November 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122130321/http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1246482--metrolinx-would-resume-go-negotiations-on-knob-hill-farms-site-for-the-right-price}}</ref> On June 20, 2016, it was announced that the line will be extended to Bowmanville. The extension is expected to open in 2024.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lakeshore East GO train service expanding 20 km to Bowmanville by 2024|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/lakeshore-east-go-train-service-expanding-20-km-to-bowmanville-by-2024-1.3643450|accessdate=20 June 2016|agency=The Canadian Press|publisher=CBC|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurrent plans call for a realignment to follow a path similar to the original one chosen for the GO ALRT project, crossing the 401 to follow the Belleville Sub mainline on the north side of the highway. There are two \"obvious\" locations for such a crossover: one is just west of the existing Oshawa station where the CP line forms a sharp bend at Thickson Road; the other is to follow the existing railbridge just east of the station where CP switches traffic for the GM plants. The latter is more difficult in theory, because of the location of the Via station directly off the east end of the tracks.\n\nThe current proposed expansion route follows the CNR rail corridor south of [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] eastward to Thickson Road in Whitby, where a new split would cross north of the highway to connect to the CPR corridor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gotransit.com/public/en/docs/ea/oshawabowmanville/AppendixE_HumanHealthRiskAssessment_Report.PDF|title=Screening level human health risk assessment (SLHHRA) of air quality impacts|work=GO Transit rail service expansion from Oshawa to Bowmnaville|authors=Intrinsik Environmental Sciences, AECOM Canada|publisher=GO Trqansit|date=January 2011|accessdate=14 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915004639/http://www.gotransit.com/public/en/docs/ea/oshawabowmanville/AppendixE_HumanHealthRiskAssessment_Report.PDF|archive-date=2014-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref><!-- page 22 (numbered); page 40 of document -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.gotransit.com/static_files/gotransit/assets/pdf/TripPlanning/FullSchedules/05012019/Table09.pdf GO Transit: Lakeshore East GO Train & Bus Service]\n\n{{GO Transit}}\n\n[[Category:GO Transit]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transport in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Transport in Durham Region]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rail line\n | box_width   = 300px\n | name        = Lakeshore East\n | color       = ee3124\n | logo        = {{rint|gotransit|rail|B|x|size=35}}\n | logo_width  =\n | logo_alt    =\n | image       = GO 558 Pulling East from Guildwood.jpg\n | image_width = 300px\n | image_alt   =\n | caption     = GO Train approaches a level crossing at Galloway Road in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n | type        = [[Commuter rail]]\n | system      = [[GO Transit#Rail|GO Train]]\n | status      = \n | locale      = [[Toronto]]; [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering]]; [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]]; [[Whitby, Ontario|Whitby]];<br>[[Oshawa]]\n | start       =\n | end         =\n | stations    = 10\n | routes      =\n | daily_ridership = 52,000 (2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/docs/pdf/board_agenda/20140905/20140905_BoardMtg_Regional_Express_Rail_EN.pdf |title=Regional  Express Rail |date=5 September 2014 |publisher=[[Metrolinx]] |accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref>\n | open        = {{Start date|1967|05|23}}\n | close       =\n | owner       = [[Metrolinx]]\n | operator    = [[GO Transit]]\n | character   =\n | depot       =\n | stock       =\n | linelength_km = 50.5\n | tracklength = \n | tracks = \n | gauge       = {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}}\n | old_gauge =\n | minradius   =\n | racksystem  =\n | routenumber =\n | electrification =\n | speed       = \n | elevation   =\n | website     =\n | map         = {{GO Transit Lakeshore East}}\n | map_state   = \n}}\n'''Lakeshore East''' is one of the seven [[commuter rail]] lines of the [[GO Transit]] system in the [[Greater Toronto Area]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It extends from [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] in [[Toronto]] to {{STN|Oshawa GO}} in [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]]. Buses from Oshawa connect to communities further east in [[Newcastle, Ontario|Newcastle]], [[Bowmanville, Ontario|Bowmanville]] and [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]].\n\nMost off-peak and some peak trains are interlined with the [[Lakeshore West line]], continuing to [[Aldershot GO Station|Aldershot]] or [[Niagara Falls station (Ontario)|Niagara Falls]].\n\n==History==\nThe Lakeshore East line is the second oldest of GO's services, opening as part of the then-unified Lakeshore line on GO's first day of operations, 23 May 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/May2007/23/c3558.html|title=GO celebrates 40 years of success|website=www.newswire.ca}}</ref> It is ten minutes younger than its twin; although the first train from [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering]] bound for Toronto left at 5:00 am that day, a 4:50 am departure from [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]] on Lakeshore West beat it into the record books.\n\nThe line initially ran along the [[CN Kingston Subdivision]] from Union to Pickering. Just prior to the opening of GO service, CN had moved much of its freight operations from downtown areas to the new [[MacMillan Yard]] north of the city. To feed freight traffic from the east into the Yard, CN built the new [[CN York Subdivision|York Subdivision]] across the top of the city (in what was then farmland) and connected the Yard to the Kingston Sub just west of Pickering at Pickering Junction. This offloaded the majority of traffic from the Kingston Sub between Pickering Junction and Union, allowing ample scheduling room for GO service. Sections of the Kingston Sub to the east of Pickering Junction remained in use as the mainline to [[Montreal]], and CN did not have capacity to allow GO traffic on these sections.\n\nGO had originally planned to address this as part of a much larger project known as [[GO-Urban]], and later, [[GO ALRT]]. GO ALRT would have used a new electric train car running on a dedicated right-of-way between Pickering and its terminus to the east of Harmony Road on the far eastern edge of [[Oshawa]]. ALRT was to have followed the CN lines east to Whitby, then across the 401 to follow the [[Canadian Pacific Railway|CP]] [[CP Belleville Subdivision|Belleville Sub]], which runs in parallel on the north side of the 401. Stations would be built at Pickering, Ajax, Whitby, Hopkins (west edge of Oshawa), Simcoe (downtown Oshawa), Oshawa east (at Stevenson) and finally Harmony. First proposed in 1982, ALRT lived for only a short time before it was cancelled in 1985 with a change of government.\n\nInstead, the basic alignment planned for ALRT from Pickering to Oshawa was laid using conventional track, splitting off at Pickering Junction and running under the York Sub bridge over the 401 in a complex basket weave. It ran along the original ALRT layout to Whitby, but abandoned the 401 overpass and instead continued along the CN lines to the current [[Oshawa GO Station]] on the far western edge of town. The new lines were laid in sections, reaching Oshawa in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gotransitmotive.bravehost.com/RosterStats/significantdates.htm |title=Significant dates in GO Transit |access-date=2018-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195027/http://gotransitmotive.bravehost.com/RosterStats/significantdates.htm |archive-date=2016-03-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Until 29 December 2006, weekend and holiday trains still ended in Pickering,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transit.toronto.on.ca/regional/2101.shtml |title=GO Transit's Lakeshore Line|website=Transit Toronto|author1=Daniel Garcia|author2=James Bow|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref> but service is now offered along the entire route every day of the year.\n\nIn December 1993, GO Transit initiated a program for the eastward expansion of the Lakeshore East line, for which it received approval in 1994.<ref name=\"Cole\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oshawaexpress.ca/viewposting.php?view=411|title=GO Train expansion - Will all be 'all aboard?'|last=Cole|first=Lindsay|newspaper=The Oshawa Express|date=|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> GO Transit undertook a study to determine whether to use the tracks of [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] or [[Canadian National Railway]].<ref name=\"Cole\" />\n\nMetrolinx purchased the Kingston Sub between Pickering Junction and Union on 31 March 2011.<ref name=\"CNtoGO\">{{cite news|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110330/go-metrolinx-pickering-toronto-canadian-national-railway-110330/20110330?hub=TorontoNewHome|title=GO owner buys rail line between T.O. and Pickering|publisher=CTV Toronto (CTVGlobeMedia) |date=30 March 2011|accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref> This means that GO now completely owns the Lakeshore East, Newmarket/Barrie and Stouffville corridors.\n\nOn 29 June 2013, off-peak service was improved to every 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/04/19/go_trains_to_run_every_30_minutes_all_day_on_lakeshore_lines.html|title=GO trains to run every 30 minutes all day on Lakeshore lines|last=Kalinowski|first=Tess|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers|date=19 April 2013|accessdate=2013-04-19}}</ref>  On 24 September 2018, weekday mid-day service frequency was improved again, now operating every 15 minutes.  <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/go-trains-lakeshore-service-increase-1.4831511|title=GO trains on Lakeshore lines to run more often|last=|first=|newspaper=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=20 September 2018|accessdate=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n==Service==\nAs of September 2018, local service operates every 15 minutes on weekdays mid-day, and every 30 minutes during other periods.  In addition to local service, there are up to 4 express trains per hour during weekday peak periods.<ref name=2018Schedule>{{cite web |url=https://www.gotransit.com/static_files/gotransit/assets/pdf/TripPlanning/FullSchedules/FS11012020/Table09.pdf |title=Lakeshore East Line 2020 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=11 January 2020 |website= |publisher=GO Transit |access-date=20 January 2020 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Station list==\n\nMost off-peak trains, as well as some peak trains, continue on to the Lakeshore West corridor after stopping at Union; there is no need to change trains to continue on to destinations on the Lakeshore West line.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Station\n!colspan=2|Municipality\n! Connections\n! Notes\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Bowmanville}}''\n|rowspan=8|[[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Clarington]]\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Darlington}}''\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Oshawa Central}}''\n|rowspan=3|[[Oshawa]]\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! ''{{GOs|Thornton's Corners}}''\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! {{GOs|Oshawa}}\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|rail}} {{rint|ca|via}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Whitby}}\n| [[Whitby, Ontario|Whitby]]\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Ajax}}\n| [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]]\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Pickering}}\n| [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering]]\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Rouge Hill}}\n|colspan=2 rowspan=7|[[Toronto]]\n| {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]], [[Durham Region Transit|DRT]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Guildwood}}\n| {{rint|rail}} {{rint|ca|via}}<br>{{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Eglinton}}\n| {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Scarborough}}\n| {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! {{GOs|Danforth}}\n| {{rint|toronto|subway|2}}<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar}} {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]]\n| \n|-\n! ''East Harbour''\n| TBD\n| ''Proposed station''\n|-\n! [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union]]\n|  {{rint|gotransit|rail|A}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|C|x}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|D|x}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|F|x}} {{rint|gotransit|rail|E|x}}  {{rint|gotransit|rail|G|x}} {{rint|gotransit|bus}}<br>{{rint|rail}} {{rint|us|amtrak}} {{rint|toronto|up}} {{rint|ca|via}} <br> {{rint|toronto|subway|1}}<br> {{rint|toronto|streetcar}} {{rint|toronto|bus}} [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]] \n|Through service to Lakeshore West line\n|}\n\n==Expansion==\nIn 2008, Metrolinx published its regional transportation entitled ''[[The Big Move]]''. As part of this, the agency identified an express all-day service between Hamilton and Oshawa (via Toronto Union) as one of its top 15 priorities.<ref>[http://www.metrolinx.com/thebigmove/lookingforward/5_2_first15years.html The Big Move] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618135517/http://www.metrolinx.com/thebigmove/lookingforward/5_2_first15years.html |date=2010-06-18 }}, Section 5.2: The first 15 years. Retrieved July 23, 2010</ref> Metrolinx has also committed to eventually providing service every 15 minutes on the line, as well as electrifying railways. This project, dubbed [[GO Regional Express Rail|Regional Express Rail]], is expected to reduce some trip times by 20%.<ref name=\"RER LW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/regionalplanning/rer/rer_lsw.aspx|title=Metrolinx Regional Express Rail \u2013 Lakeshore West GO line|website=www.metrolinx.com}}</ref><ref name=TheStar-2015-04-17>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/transportation/2015/04/17/go-to-add-30-per-cent-more-trains-in-next-5-years-s.html |title=GO to add almost 50 per cent more trains in next 5 years |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |author=Tess Kalinowski, Transportation reporter |date={{date|2015-04-17}} |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref>\nContinued growth of the Oshawa area has led to renewed calls for expansion of the Lakeshore East line, this time all the way to [[Bowmanville, Ontario|Bowmanville]]. Possible station stops have been identified near Stevenson Road, Bloor Street, Courtice Road, and two locations in Bowmanville. There were plans to convert a building that used to be a [[Knob Hill Farms]] grocery store into a GO train station located near Simcoe Street, but the plans to build a station there have been scrapped due to environmental concerns and the challenge of reaching a fair purchase price with the property owner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1243892--metrolinx-derails-plans-for-oshawa-go-station|title=Metrolinx derails plans for Oshawa GO station |date=November 14, 2011|website=DurhamRegion.com |first=Jillian|last=Follert|archive-date=May 23, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523195140/http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1243892--metrolinx-derails-plans-for-oshawa-go-station}}</ref> However, negotiations for a station in downtown Oshawa could be reconsidered if both sides could come to an agreement on a fair purchase price for the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1246482--metrolinx-would-resume-go-negotiations-on-knob-hill-farms-site-for-the-right-price|title=Metrolinx would resume GO negotiations on Knob Hill Farms site for the right price |date=November 18, 2011|first=Jillian|last=Follert|website=DurhamRegion.com |archive-date=November 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122130321/http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1246482--metrolinx-would-resume-go-negotiations-on-knob-hill-farms-site-for-the-right-price}}</ref> On June 20, 2016, it was announced that the line will be extended to Bowmanville. The extension is expected to open in 2024.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lakeshore East GO train service expanding 20 km to Bowmanville by 2024|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/lakeshore-east-go-train-service-expanding-20-km-to-bowmanville-by-2024-1.3643450|accessdate=20 June 2016|agency=The Canadian Press|publisher=CBC|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurrent plans call for a realignment to follow a path similar to the original one chosen for the GO ALRT project, crossing the 401 to follow the Belleville Sub mainline on the north side of the highway. There are two \"obvious\" locations for such a crossover: one is just west of the existing Oshawa station where the CP line forms a sharp bend at Thickson Road; the other is to follow the existing railbridge just east of the station where CP switches traffic for the GM plants. The latter is more difficult in theory, because of the location of the Via station directly off the east end of the tracks.\n\nThe current proposed expansion route follows the CNR rail corridor south of [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] eastward to Thickson Road in Whitby, where a new split would cross north of the highway to connect to the CPR corridor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gotransit.com/public/en/docs/ea/oshawabowmanville/AppendixE_HumanHealthRiskAssessment_Report.PDF|title=Screening level human health risk assessment (SLHHRA) of air quality impacts|work=GO Transit rail service expansion from Oshawa to Bowmnaville|authors=Intrinsik Environmental Sciences, AECOM Canada|publisher=GO Trqansit|date=January 2011|accessdate=14 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915004639/http://www.gotransit.com/public/en/docs/ea/oshawabowmanville/AppendixE_HumanHealthRiskAssessment_Report.PDF|archive-date=2014-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref><!-- page 22 (numbered); page 40 of document -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.gotransit.com/static_files/gotransit/assets/pdf/TripPlanning/FullSchedules/05012019/Table09.pdf GO Transit: Lakeshore East GO Train & Bus Service]\n\n{{GO Transit}}\n\n[[Category:GO Transit]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transport in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Transport in Durham Region]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Zebuready", "label": "safe", "comment": "Greater Toronto Area, Ontario, Canada", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakeshore_East_line"}
{"title_page": "Jake Daubert", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Jake Daubert\n|image=Jake Daubert.jpg\n|position=[[First baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1884|4|7}}\n|birth_place=[[Shamokin, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1924|10|9|1884|4|7}}\n|death_place=[[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Left\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 14\n|debutyear=1910\n|debutteam=Brooklyn Superbas\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=September 20\n|finalyear=1924\n|finalteam=Cincinnati Reds\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.303\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=56\n|stat4label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=722\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=2,326\n|teams=\n* [[Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn Superbas / Dodgers / Robins]] ({{mlby|1910}}\u2013{{mlby|1918}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|1919}}\u2013{{mlby|1924}})\n|highlights=\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1919}})\n* [[NL MVP]] (1913)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|NL batting champion]] (1913, 1914)\n* [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]]\n}}\n'''Jacob Ellsworth Daubert''' (April 7, 1884 \u2013 October 9, 1924) was an American [[first baseman]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for the [[Brooklyn Superbas]]<ref>The team also went by the nicknames Dodgers and Robins during Daubert's time with Brooklyn.</ref> and [[Cincinnati Reds]]. His career lasted from 1910 until his death in 1924.\n\nDaubert was recognized throughout his career for his performance on the field. He won the 1913 and 1914 National League [[batting average (baseball)|batting titles]] and the 1913 [[MLB Most Valuable Player Award|Chalmers Award]]. Between 1911 and 1919, ''The Baseball Magazine'' named him to their All-American team seven times.<ref>Deadball Era Resources. [http://world.std.com/~pgw/Deadball/all.america.html \"The Baseball Magazine All American Teams\"]. Retrieved November 9, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060128122643/http://world.std.com/~pgw/Deadball/all.america.html |date=January 28, 2006 }}</ref> Baseball historian William C. Kashatus observed that Daubert was \"a steady .300 hitter for 10 years of the [[Deadball Era]]\" who \"never fielded below the .989 mark.\"<ref>Kashatus (2002), pp. 94&ndash;95.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDaubert was born in [[Shamokin, Pennsylvania]] to Jacob and Sarah Daubert. The lack of [[Child labor laws in the United States|child labor laws]] enabled Daubert to go to work early in his life. In 1895, at the age of eleven, the young Daubert joined his father and two brothers at work in the local [[coal mine]]s.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\">{{cite web| title = Jake Daubert | work = TheDeadballEra.com | first=Jim | last=Sandoval | url=http://www.thedeadballera.com/NiceGuys_Daubert_Jake.htm | accessdate = November 9, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, Daubert left his job at the mines and signed a contract with a baseball team in [[Lykens, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"thebaseballpage\">{{cite web|title=Jake Daubert |work=TheBaseballPage.com |url=http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/daubeja01.php |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060507084734/http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/daubeja01.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 7, 2006 |accessdate=April 7, 2007 }}</ref> He was originally a [[pitcher]] on the team before he converted to first base.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> At the end of the 1906 season, Daubert left Pennsylvania and traveled west to Ohio. There, he spent the 1907 season on teams in [[Kane, Pennsylvania]] and [[Marion, Ohio]].<ref name=\"thebaseballpage\"/>\n\n==Baseball career==\n[[Image:Jake Daubert Baseball Card.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Daubert on a 1911 [[American Tobacco Company]] [[baseball card]]]]\nIn 1908, Daubert was signed by the [[Cleveland Indians]]. However, Daubert never played for Cleveland as they released him shortly thereafter. He left Cleveland and signed with the [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] club of the [[Southern Association]]. He spent the remainder of the season with Nashville.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/>\n\nDaubert returned to Ohio for the start of the 1909 season. After playing the first part of the season with [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] of the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]], Daubert went back to Tennessee and joined the [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] club. Like Nashville, Memphis' team played in the Southern Association. While playing for Memphis, Larry Sutton, a scout for the Brooklyn Dodgers, observed his play. Shortly thereafter, the Dodgers purchased Daubert's contract and brought him to Brooklyn for the 1910 season.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/>\n\nWhile Daubert hit just .264 in 1910, he hit over .300 in each of the next six seasons. On May 6, 1910, Daubert recorded 21 [[putout]]s in a single game, one short of the major league record.<ref>[http://nyc.sabr.org/newsletters/Summer%202001.pdf SABR] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106035956/http://nyc.sabr.org/newsletters/Summer%202001.pdf |date=November 6, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1911 and 1912, Daubert placed ninth and eighth in the Chalmers Award voting.<ref>The Chalmers Award was Major League Baseball's first iteration of the Most Valuable Player Award.</ref><ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/daubeja01.shtml \"Jake Daubert Statistics and History\"]. ''baseball-reference.com''. Retrieved February 13, 2011.</ref> The following year, he won the award. On August 15, 1914, Daubert tied [[Cy Seymour]]'s MLB record with four [[sacrifice bunt]]s in one game.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/mcall/access/43573324.html?dids=43573324:43573324&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+30%2C+1999&author=DON+BOSTROM%2C+The+Morning+Call&pub=Morning+Call&desc=SUN+KING+OGEA+IS+MORE+THAN+OK+*+HE+TOSSES+SEVEN+INNINGS+OF+SIX-+HIT+BALL+AND+SETS+UP+PHILS+WITH+THREE+SACRIFICE+BUNTS.&pqatl=google | work=Morning Call | first=Don | last=Bostrom | title=Sun King Ogea Is More Than Ok * He Tosses Seven Innings Of Six- Hit Ball And Sets Up Phils With Three Sacrifice Bunts | date=July 30, 1999}}</ref> In 1916 he batted .316 and Brooklyn won their first NL pennant. His season ended in disappointment, however, after he hit only .176 in the [[1916 World Series]] and Brooklyn lost the series to the [[Boston Red Sox]].\n\nDaubert hit .261 in 1917, but the following year he hit .308 and led the NL in [[Triple (baseball)|triples]]. When the season was cut short due to World War I and the [[Spanish flu|Spanish flu epidemic]], major league owners prorated player salaries. Daubert, who had been among the founding members of the [[Major League Baseball Players Association|Players' Fraternity]], sued for the balance of his salary. Eventually, Jake recovered most of the $2,150 he was due.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> After the dispute started, Brooklyn owner [[Charles Ebbets (baseball)|Charles Ebbets]] traded him to Cincinnati for outfielder [[Tommy Griffith]]. Once in Cincinnati, Daubert served as the Reds' [[Captain (sports)|captain]] for the remainder of his career.<ref name=\"thebaseballpage\"/>\n\nIn 1919, although he hit only .276, Daubert was second in the league in [[Run (baseball)|runs scored]] and third in triples. The Reds won their first pennant since the inaugural season of the [[American Association (19th century)|American Association]] in 1882. In the [[1919 World Series]], noted for the [[Black Sox Scandal]], he batted .241. In the 9-1 Game One victory, he had three hits, including a triple, and he had two [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] and scored twice in the final 10-5 victory in the decisive Game Eight.\n\nDaubert hit over .300 in the next three seasons. In 1922, Daubert hit for a .336 average, led the NL in triples and had a career-high 12 [[home run]]s. By 1923, at age 39, he was the oldest regular position player in the major leagues,<ref name=\"br-NL-1923\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1923.shtml |title=1923 National League Statistics and Awards |accessdate=April 18, 2007 |work=Baseball-Reference.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429002528/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1923.shtml |archivedate=April 29, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and he hit .292 that season.\n\nDaubert also excelled in sacrifice hits. His career total of 392 sacrifice hits is second in MLB history, behind Hall of Famer [[Eddie Collins]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/SH_career.shtml Career Leaders &amp; Records for Sac. Hits] ''Baseball-Reference.com''</ref>\n\nIn his career, he had 56 home runs, 1,117 runs, 722 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]], 250 [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] and 251 [[stolen base]]s. He recorded a .991 [[fielding percentage]]. When he left Brooklyn for Cincinnati, Daubert held the Brooklyn franchise record for games played at first base (1,206). The record was broken by [[Gil Hodges]] in 1956.\n\n==Baseball unionization efforts==\nDaubert was a trailblazer in baseball's unionization movement, a controversial role that may have been a factor in his omission from the Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/> In 1913, he served as vice president of the Baseball Players' Fraternity, which petitioned the National Baseball Commission for improved labor conditions.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/> The petition included the following requests: 1) permission for players to negotiate with any team following their unconditional release, 2) a guarantee that clubs would provide players with 10 days' notice before releasing them unconditionally, 3) a guarantee that clubs would inform players of the terms of their contract when they are sent to another team, 4) a guarantee that a veteran players would not be sent to the minor leagues when his services are of interest to another major league club, 5) a guarantee that clubs would furnish uniforms and shoes to players free of charge, 6) a guarantee that clubs would provide traveling expenses to players between their homes and spring training camps, and 7) that players should receive written notice concerning any fine or suspension levied against them.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\">Kashatus (2002), p. 95.</ref>\n\nAlthough Daubert was unsuccessful in pressuring the commissioners to accept the terms of the fledgling baseball union's petition, he lobbied continuously for his own interests as a player, thereby earning a reputation as a \"troublemaker\" within the baseball establishment.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/> A salary dispute with the [[Charles Ebbets (baseball)|Charles Ebbets]], owner of the Dodgers, was a major factor in Daubert's transfer to Cincinnati in 1919.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/>\n\n==Life outside baseball & death==\nWhile Daubert was in Brooklyn, he was nominated for city [[Alderman#In the United States|Alderman]].<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> He also spent time as a businessman and invested in several business ventures. His holdings included a pool hall, a cigar business, a semi-pro baseball team, a moving picture business, and a [[coal breaker]]. His most profitable business was reportedly the coal breaker, which was located in his hometown.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/>\n\nDaubert left the Reds late in the 1924 season after falling ill during a road trip to New York.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\">{{cite web|title=The Obit for Jake Daubert |work=TheDeadBallEra.com |url=http://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Daubert.Jake.Obit.html |accessdate=November 10, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113003614/http://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Daubert.Jake.Obit.html |archivedate=November 13, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Against his doctor's advice, he returned to play in the team's final home game of the season.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> On October 2, he had an [[appendectomy]] performed by Dr. Harry H. Hines, the Reds' team doctor.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> Complications from the operation arose, and a [[blood transfusion]] did not improve his health.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> He died one week after the operation in [[Cincinnati]], with the doctor citing \"exhaustion, resulting in indigestion, [as] the immediate cause of death\".<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> It was later discovered that Daubert suffered from a hereditary blood disorder called [[Spherocytosis|hemolytic spherocytosis]], which contributed to his death.<ref>[http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=966&pid=3274/ Jake Daubert] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> He was interred at the [[Charles Baber Cemetery]] in [[Pottsville, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Jake Daubert | work = Retrosheet.org | url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/Pdaubj101.htm | accessdate = November 10, 2006 }}</ref> Daubert was survived by his wife Gertrude, his son George, and his daughter Louisa.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> As of 2019, he remains the oldest ballplayer to die while in the majors.\n\nDuring his career, Daubert compiled a .303 lifetime batting average. At the time of his death, he ranked among the major league career leaders in games (4th, 2,001), putouts (4th, 19,634), [[Assist (baseball)|assists]] (5th, 1,128), [[total chances]] (4th, 20,943) and [[double play]]s (3rd, 1,199) at first base; he was also among the NL's leaders in hits (7th, 2,326), triples (9th, 165), [[at bat]]s (9th, 7,673), [[games played]] (10th, 2,014) and [[total bases]] (10th, 3,074). Daubert currently holds the NL record for most [[sacrifice hit]]s (392). He was inducted into the [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]] in 1966<ref>{{cite web| title = Reds Hall of Famers | work = Cincinnati.Reds.MLB.com | url=http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/cin/ballpark/museum/hofers.jsp#daubert | accessdate = April 17, 2007 }}</ref> and the Brooklyn Dodgers Hall of Fame in 1990.<ref>{{cite web | title = Brooklyn Dodgers Hall of Fame Inductees | work = Ebbets-Field.com | url = http://www.ebbets-field.com/MartyAdler/HallofFame.htm | accessdate = April 17, 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927203728/http://www.ebbets-field.com/MartyAdler/HallofFame.htm | archivedate = September 27, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[List of baseball players who died during their careers]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career triples leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career stolen bases leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual triples leaders]]\n\n==References==\n;Bibliography\n* ''Baseball: The Biographical Encyclopedia'' (2000). Kingston, New York: Total/Sports Illustrated. {{ISBN|1-892129-34-5}}.\n* Kashatus, William C. (2002). ''Diamonds in the Coalfields: 21 Remarkable Baseball Players, Managers, and Umpires from Northeast Pennsylvania''. Jefferson, North Carolina: McFarland & Company. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-1176-4}}.\n\n;In-line citations\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat}}\n{{Baseballstats|br=d/daubeja01|brm=dauber001jac}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Cincinnati Reds team captains}}\n{{1919 Cincinnati Reds}}\n{{Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame}}\n{{NL Chalmers Award}}\n{{NL batting title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daubert, Jake}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first basemen]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Robins players]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Superbas players]]\n[[Category:Burials at Charles Baber Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National League batting champions]]\n[[Category:Kane Mountaineers players]]\n[[Category:Marion Moguls players]]\n[[Category:Nashville Vols players]]\n[[Category:Memphis Turtles players]]\n[[Category:Toledo Mud Hens players]]\n[[Category:People from Shamokin, Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Jake Daubert\n|image=Jake Daubert.jpg\n|position=[[First baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1884|4|7}}\n|birth_place=[[Shamokin, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1924|10|9|1884|4|7}}\n|death_place=[[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Left\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 14\n|debutyear=1910\n|debutteam=Brooklyn Superbas\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=September 20\n|finalyear=1924\n|finalteam=Cincinnati Reds\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.303\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=56\n|stat4label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=722\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=2,326\n|teams=\n* [[Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn Superbas / Dodgers / Robins]] ({{mlby|1910}}\u2013{{mlby|1918}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|1919}}\u2013{{mlby|1924}})\n|highlights=\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1919}})\n* [[NL MVP]] (1913)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|NL batting champion]] (1913, 1914)\n* [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]]\n}}\n'''Jacob Ellsworth Daubert''' (April 7, 1884 \u2013 October 9, 1924) was an American [[first baseman]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for the [[Brooklyn Superbas]]<ref>The team also went by the nicknames Dodgers and Robins during Daubert's time with Brooklyn.</ref> and [[Cincinnati Reds]]. His career lasted from 1910 until his death in 1924.\n\nDaubert was recognized throughout his career for his performance on the field. He won the 1913 and 1914 National League [[batting average (baseball)|batting titles]] and the 1913 [[MLB Most Valuable Player Award|Chalmers Award]]. Between 1911 and 1919, ''The Baseball Magazine'' named him to their All-American team seven times.<ref>Deadball Era Resources. [http://world.std.com/~pgw/Deadball/all.america.html \"The Baseball Magazine All American Teams\"]. Retrieved November 9, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060128122643/http://world.std.com/~pgw/Deadball/all.america.html |date=January 28, 2006 }}</ref> Baseball historian William C. Kashatus observed that Daubert was \"a steady .300 hitter for 10 years of the [[Deadball Era]]\" who \"never fielded below the .989 mark.\"<ref>Kashatus (2002), pp. 94&ndash;95.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDaubert was born in [[Shamokin, Pennsylvania]] to Jacob and Sarah Daubert. The lack of [[Child labor laws in the United States|child labor laws]] enabled Daubert to go to work early in his life. In 1895, at the age of eleven, the young Daubert joined his father and two brothers at work in the local [[coal mine]]s.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\">{{cite web| title = Jake Daubert | work = TheDeadballEra.com | first=Jim | last=Sandoval | url=http://www.thedeadballera.com/NiceGuys_Daubert_Jake.htm | accessdate = November 9, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, Daubert left his job at the mines and signed a contract with a baseball team in [[Lykens, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"thebaseballpage\">{{cite web|title=Jake Daubert |work=TheBaseballPage.com |url=http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/daubeja01.php |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060507084734/http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/daubeja01.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 7, 2006 |accessdate=April 7, 2007 }}</ref> He was originally a [[pitcher]] on the team before he converted to first base.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> At the end of the 1906 season, Daubert left Pennsylvania and traveled west to Ohio. There, he spent the 1907 season on teams in [[Kane, Pennsylvania]] and [[Marion, Ohio]].<ref name=\"thebaseballpage\"/>\n\n==Baseball career==\n[[Image:Jake Daubert Baseball Card.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Daubert on a 1911 [[American Tobacco Company]] [[baseball card]]]]\nIn 1908, Daubert was signed by the [[Cleveland Indians]]. However, Daubert never played for Cleveland as they released him shortly thereafter. He left Cleveland and signed with the [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] club of the [[Southern Association]]. He spent the remainder of the season with Nashville.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/>\n\nDaubert returned to Ohio for the start of the 1909 season. After playing the first part of the season with [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] of the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]], Daubert went back to Tennessee and joined the [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] club. Like Nashville, Memphis' team played in the Southern Association. While playing for Memphis, Larry Sutton, a scout for the Brooklyn Dodgers, observed his play. Shortly thereafter, the Dodgers purchased Daubert's contract and brought him to Brooklyn for the 1910 season.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/>\n\nWhile Daubert hit just .264 in 1910, he hit over .300 in each of the next six seasons. On May 6, 1910, Daubert recorded 21 [[putout]]s in a single game, one short of the major league record.<ref>[http://nyc.sabr.org/newsletters/Summer%202001.pdf SABR] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106035956/http://nyc.sabr.org/newsletters/Summer%202001.pdf |date=November 6, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1911 and 1912, Daubert placed ninth and eighth in the Chalmers Award voting.<ref>The Chalmers Award was Major League Baseball's first iteration of the Most Valuable Player Award.</ref><ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/daubeja01.shtml \"Jake Daubert Statistics and History\"]. ''baseball-reference.com''. Retrieved February 13, 2011.</ref> The following year, he won the award. On August 15, 1914, Daubert tied [[Cy Seymour]]'s MLB record with four [[sacrifice bunt]]s in one game.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/mcall/access/43573324.html?dids=43573324:43573324&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+30%2C+1999&author=DON+BOSTROM%2C+The+Morning+Call&pub=Morning+Call&desc=SUN+KING+OGEA+IS+MORE+THAN+OK+*+HE+TOSSES+SEVEN+INNINGS+OF+SIX-+HIT+BALL+AND+SETS+UP+PHILS+WITH+THREE+SACRIFICE+BUNTS.&pqatl=google | work=Morning Call | first=Don | last=Bostrom | title=Sun King Ogea Is More Than Ok * He Tosses Seven Innings Of Six- Hit Ball And Sets Up Phils With Three Sacrifice Bunts | date=July 30, 1999}}</ref> In 1916 he batted .316 and Brooklyn won their first NL pennant. His season ended in disappointment, however, after he hit only .176 in the [[1916 World Series]] and Brooklyn lost the series to the [[Boston Red Sox]].\n\nDaubert hit .261 in 1917, but the following year he hit .308 and led the NL in [[Triple (baseball)|triples]]. When the season was cut short due to World War I and the [[Spanish flu|Spanish flu epidemic]], major league owners prorated player salaries. Daubert, who had been among the founding members of the [[Major League Baseball Players Association|Players' Fraternity]], sued for the balance of his salary. Eventually, Jake recovered most of the $2,150 he was due.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> After the dispute started, Brooklyn owner [[Charles Ebbets (baseball)|Charles Ebbets]] traded him to Cincinnati for outfielder [[Tommy Griffith]]. Once in Cincinnati, Daubert served as the Reds' [[Captain (sports)|captain]] for the remainder of his career.<ref name=\"thebaseballpage\"/>\n\nIn 1919, although he hit only .276, Daubert was second in the league in [[Run (baseball)|runs scored]] and third in triples. The Reds won their first pennant since the inaugural season of the [[American Association (19th century)|American Association]] in 1882. In the [[1919 World Series]], noted for the [[Black Sox Scandal]], he batted .241. In the 9-1 Game One victory, he had three hits, including a triple, and he had two [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] and scored twice in the final 10-5 victory in the decisive Game Eight.\n\nDaubert hit over .300 in the next three seasons. In 1922, Daubert hit for a .336 average, led the NL in triples and had a career-high 12 [[home run]]s. By 1923, at age 39, he was the oldest regular position player in the major leagues,<ref name=\"br-NL-1923\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1923.shtml |title=1923 National League Statistics and Awards |accessdate=April 18, 2007 |work=Baseball-Reference.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429002528/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1923.shtml |archivedate=April 29, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and he hit .292 that season.\n\nDaubert also excelled in sacrifice hits. His career total of 392 sacrifice hits is second in MLB history, behind Hall of Famer [[Eddie Collins]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/SH_career.shtml Career Leaders &amp; Records for Sac. Hits] ''Baseball-Reference.com''</ref>\n\nIn his career, he had 56 home runs, 1117 runs, 722 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]], 250 [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] and 251 [[stolen base]]s. He recorded a .991 [[fielding percentage]]. When he left Brooklyn for Cincinnati, Daubert held the Brooklyn franchise record for games played at first base (1206). The record was broken by [[Gil Hodges]] in 1956.\n\n==Baseball unionization efforts==\nDaubert was a trailblazer in baseball's unionization movement, a controversial role that may have been a factor in his omission from the Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/> In 1913, he served as vice president of the Baseball Players' Fraternity, which petitioned the National Baseball Commission for improved labor conditions.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/> The petition included the following requests: 1) permission for players to negotiate with any team following their unconditional release, 2) a guarantee that clubs would provide players with 10 days' notice before releasing them unconditionally, 3) a guarantee that clubs would inform players of the terms of their contract when they are sent to another team, 4) a guarantee that a veteran players would not be sent to the minor leagues when his services are of interest to another major league club, 5) a guarantee that clubs would furnish uniforms and shoes to players free of charge, 6) a guarantee that clubs would provide traveling expenses to players between their homes and spring training camps, and 7) that players should receive written notice concerning any fine or suspension levied against them.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\">Kashatus (2002), p. 95.</ref>\n\nAlthough Daubert was unsuccessful in pressuring the commissioners to accept the terms of the fledgling baseball union's petition, he lobbied continuously for his own interests as a player, thereby earning a reputation as a \"troublemaker\" within the baseball establishment.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/> A salary dispute with the [[Charles Ebbets (baseball)|Charles Ebbets]], owner of the Dodgers, was a major factor in Daubert's transfer to Cincinnati in 1919.<ref name=\"kashatus94-95\"/>\n\n==Life outside baseball & death==\nWhile Daubert was in Brooklyn, he was nominated for city [[Alderman#In the United States|Alderman]].<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> He also spent time as a businessman and invested in several business ventures. His holdings included a pool hall, a cigar business, a semi-pro baseball team, a moving picture business, and a [[coal breaker]]. His most profitable business was reportedly the coal breaker, which was located in his hometown.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/>\n\nDaubert left the Reds late in the 1924 season after falling ill during a road trip to New York.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\">{{cite web|title=The Obit for Jake Daubert |work=TheDeadBallEra.com |url=http://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Daubert.Jake.Obit.html |accessdate=November 10, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113003614/http://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Daubert.Jake.Obit.html |archivedate=November 13, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Against his doctor's advice, he returned to play in the team's final home game of the season.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> On October 2, he had an [[appendectomy]] performed by Dr. Harry H. Hines, the Reds' team doctor.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> Complications from the operation arose, and a [[blood transfusion]] did not improve his health.<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> He died one week after the operation in [[Cincinnati]], with the doctor citing \"exhaustion, resulting in indigestion, [as] the immediate cause of death\".<ref name=\"deadballeraobit\"/> It was later discovered that Daubert suffered from a hereditary blood disorder called [[Spherocytosis|hemolytic spherocytosis]], which contributed to his death.<ref>[http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=966&pid=3274/ Jake Daubert] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> He was interred at the [[Charles Baber Cemetery]] in [[Pottsville, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Jake Daubert | work = Retrosheet.org | url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/Pdaubj101.htm | accessdate = November 10, 2006 }}</ref> Daubert was survived by his wife Gertrude, his son George, and his daughter Louisa.<ref name=\"thedeadballera\"/> As of 2019, he remains the oldest ballplayer to die while in the majors.\n\nDuring his career, Daubert compiled a .303 lifetime batting average. At the time of his death, he ranked among the major league career leaders in games (4th, 2001), putouts (4th, 19634), [[Assist (baseball)|assists]] (5th, 1128), [[total chances]] (4th, 20943) and [[double play]]s (3rd, 1199) at first base; he was also among the NL's leaders in hits (7th, 2326), triples (9th, 165), [[at bat]]s (9th, 7673), [[games played]] (10th, 2014) and [[total bases]] (10th, 3074). Daubert currently holds the NL record for most [[sacrifice hit]]s (392). He was inducted into the [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]] in 1966<ref>{{cite web| title = Reds Hall of Famers | work = Cincinnati.Reds.MLB.com | url=http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/cin/ballpark/museum/hofers.jsp#daubert | accessdate = April 17, 2007 }}</ref> and the Brooklyn Dodgers Hall of Fame in 1990.<ref>{{cite web | title = Brooklyn Dodgers Hall of Fame Inductees | work = Ebbets-Field.com | url = http://www.ebbets-field.com/MartyAdler/HallofFame.htm | accessdate = April 17, 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927203728/http://www.ebbets-field.com/MartyAdler/HallofFame.htm | archivedate = September 27, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[List of baseball players who died during their careers]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career triples leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career stolen bases leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual triples leaders]]\n\n==References==\n;Bibliography\n* ''Baseball: The Biographical Encyclopedia'' (2000). Kingston, New York: Total/Sports Illustrated. {{ISBN|1-892129-34-5}}.\n* Kashatus, William C. (2002). ''Diamonds in the Coalfields: 21 Remarkable Baseball Players, Managers, and Umpires from Northeast Pennsylvania''. Jefferson, North Carolina: McFarland & Company. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-1176-4}}.\n\n;In-line citations\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat}}\n{{Baseballstats|br=d/daubeja01|brm=dauber001jac}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Cincinnati Reds team captains}}\n{{1919 Cincinnati Reds}}\n{{Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame}}\n{{NL Chalmers Award}}\n{{NL batting title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daubert, Jake}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first basemen]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Robins players]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Superbas players]]\n[[Category:Burials at Charles Baber Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National League batting champions]]\n[[Category:Kane Mountaineers players]]\n[[Category:Marion Moguls players]]\n[[Category:Nashville Vols players]]\n[[Category:Memphis Turtles players]]\n[[Category:Toledo Mud Hens players]]\n[[Category:People from Shamokin, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "AuH2ORepublican", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jake_Daubert"}
{"title_page": "Masti (film series)", "text_new": "{{update|date=July 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Masti series\n| image = Riteish Deshmukh, Aftab Shivdasani & Vivek Oberoi at audio release of 'Grand Masti' at R-City Mall.jpg\n| caption = [[Ritesh Deshmukh]], [[Aftab Shivdasani]] and [[Vivek Oberoi]], the three leading actors of the series.\n| director       = [[Indra Kumar]]\n| producer       = Ashok Thakeria<br />[[Ekta Kapoor]]<br />{{small|('''Great Grand Masti''')}}\n| writer         = [[Bhavani Iyer]]<br />{{small|('''Masti''')}} <br> [[Milap Zaveri]]<br />{{small|('''Grand Masti''')}}<br> [[Tushar Hiranandani]] <br />{{small|('''Grand Masti''', '''Great Grand Masti''')}}\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = [[Indra Kumar]]\n| starring       = [[Vivek Oberoi]]<br>[[Aftab Shivdasani]]<br>[[Ritesh Deshmukh]]\n| music          = [[Anand Raj Anand]]<br />{{small|('''Masti''')}}<br> [[Sanjeev-Darshan]] <br />{{small|('''Grand Masti''', '''Great Grand Masti''')}}<br /> Sharab-Toshi<br> [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] <br />{{small|('''Great Grand Masti''')}}\n| cinematography = [[Mazhar Kamran]] <br />{{small|('''Masti''')}} <br> Rituraj Narain <br />{{small|('''Grand Masti''')}}<br>Nigam Bomzan <br />{{small|('''Great Grand Masti''')}}\n| editing        = Sanjay Sankla\n| studio         = Maruti International<br>[[Balaji Motion Pictures]]<br />{{small|('''Great Grand Masti''')}}\n| distributor    = [[SLB Films]] <br />{{small|('''Masti''')}} <br> Maruti International <br />{{small|('''Grand Masti''')}}<br>[[Balaji Motion Pictures]]<br />{{small|('''Great Grand Masti''')}}\n| released       = ''[[Masti (2004 film)|1]]'': {{Start date|df=yes|2004|4|9}}<br />''[[Grand Masti|2]]'': {{Start date|df=yes|2013|9|13}}<br />''[[Great Grand Masti|3]]'': {{Start date|df=yes|2016|7|22}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR|79 crore}}\n| gross          = {{INR|191 crore}}\n}}\n\n'''''Masti''''' is a series of Indian adult [[comedy film]]s. The series is directed by [[Indra Kumar]] and produced by Ashok Thakeria.<ref>{{cite web | last = Jha  | first = Subhash K  | title = Masti goes over the top with lewd jokes | publisher = The Times of India | date = 10 April 2004 | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Movie_Reviews/Masti_goes_over_the_top_with_lewd_jokes/articleshow/msid-610079,curpg-1.cms | accessdate = 8 October 2008}}</ref> The series stars [[Vivek Oberoi]], [[Aftab Shivdasani]] and [[Ritesh Deshmukh]] in principal roles.<ref>{{cite web | last = Tuteja | first = Joginder | title = GRAND MASTI to take adult humour to the next level | publisher = Glamsham | date = 9 August 2012 | url = http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/12/apr/17-news-grand-masti-to-take-adult-humour-to-the-next-level-041208.asp | accessdate = 17 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Ramsubramaniam | first = Nikhil | title = Masti sequel to be called Grand Masti | publisher = Bollywood Hungama | date = 9 August 2012 | url = http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/1535281/Grand-Masti-on-hold-for-Riteish | accessdate = 7 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n\n===''Masti'' (2004)===\n{{Main article|Masti (2004 film)}}\n''Masti'' revolves around three bachelors, Meet ([[Vivek Oberoi]]), Prem ([[Aftab Shivdasani]]) and Amar ([[Ritesh Deshmukh]]). Their lives are good until they get married and their lives turn to hell. Meet marries Anchal ([[Amrita Rao]]) who is obsessively possessive about her husband. Prem marries Geeta ([[Tara Sharma]]) who is overly religious and thus their sex life suffers. Amar marries Bindiya ([[Genelia D'Souza]]) who is dominating and lives with her mother ([[Archana Puran Singh]]). The friends get together one night and try to think of a way to get away from their wives for some time and relive their fun bachelor days. The men set their sights on other women but eventually realise they have all been seeing the same girl, Monica ([[Lara Dutta]]). She blackmails them about revealing their affair to their wives for Rs. 1&nbsp;million.\n\nThe terrified men arrive at Monica's car with all the money, only to find her dead. To not be accused, they try to hide her body, interrupted by police officer Sikander ([[Ajay Devgan]]) who begins to suspect, and then starts following, them. Thereafter, the trio goes to Monica's house for further investigation. Insp. Sikander traces the three who hide at Monica's verandah. Next morning, a mysterious man finds them and reveals that he killed Monica and demands [[ransom]] to cover the crime. The trio, guilt-ridden goes to their respective wives to apologise. But the very next day, the killer traces them and chases them in a car. Unknown to them, they shoot the killer and escape but end up in jail. After their wives show up, it is revealed that it was just a prank played on them and reveals Monica is alive and the killer turns to be a police officer. The men then apologise their wives and promise to never do \"Masti\" again.\n\n===''Grand Masti'' (2013)===\n{{Main article|Grand Masti}}\nThree friends \u2013 Meet ([[Vivek Oberoi]]), Prem ([[Aftab Shivdasani]]) and Amar ([[Ritesh Deshmukh]]), who are married and don't like their wives: Meet thinks his wife Unatti ([[Karishma Tanna]]) is having an affair with her boss, Prem doesn't like it when his wife Tulsi ([[Manjari Fadnis]]) doesn't spend quality time with him and Amar hates his marital life because his wife Mamta ([[Sonalee Kulkarni]]) is more concerned about their son, Pappu.\n\nOne day, the trio receive an invite from their college, SLUTS (Sri Lalchand University of Technology And Science), to attend their college reunion. Their wives don't come with them, so the trio decide to have Grand Masti there to escape their boredom.\n\nWhen they arrive, they see the women full clothed and the boys too afraid to express their love for them. This all due to the fear of a Principal Roberts ([[Pradeep Rawat (actor)|Pradeep Rawat]]), who hangs people naked on a tree if they disagree with his rules. They find out that their former colleague, Hardik ([[Suresh Menon]]), is in the mental asylum because of the principal. Meanwhile, Prem meets one of his former teachers, Rose ([[Maryam Zakaria]]), and is attracted to her. Meet meets Marlow ([[Kainaat Arora]]) and is attracted to her. Amar meets Mary ([[Bruna Abdullah]]) and is attracted to her. The trio then goes to the girl's place to have sex with them. But just when they were about to do it, they find out that Marlow, Mary and Rose are relatives of the principal. The principal chases them down thinking they had sex with Marlow, Mary and Rose, but they get away as their wives come to spend time with them.\n\nThe trio then get an MMS showing them the footage of them having sex. Luckily, the video doesn't meet the eyes of their wives. They then find out that it was Hardik who sent them the video, and he blackmails them. Their task is to kill the principal to fulfill Hardik's revenge. They fail in killing him, so they decide to try and delete the videos off Hardik's phone. They succeed, and continue to spend their time at the reunion.\n\nIt's the last day, and the vengeful principal has put pills inside the soup which attract people to the ones they love. The trio end up being with the girls, and the principal catches them red handed. The girls then reveal that the principal is impotent. The trio then get chased by the principal along with the attracted girls, but then when the trio end up on the roof of a building, Hardik pushes the principal and the principal slides down the roof and hangs on to a bar. The trio try to save him but Hardik pushes them too and they hang onto the principal. The girls come and push Hardik off the roof and he hangs on to Meet. The trio then tell principal the truth about not having sex with Marlow, Mary and Rose. The girls try to make a rope out of their clothes, but the boys fall and end up in the hospital. The trio wives angrily ask them what exactly happened that night. Principal Roberts calmly replies that due to a misunderstood affair, their husband suffered this consequence. Shortly later, a doctor comes and informs the principal that he is no more impotent since the blood now properly flows all over his body due to the pressure generated while hanging on the bar. Hardik marries Marlow and the film ends up Roberts, Hardik and the trio about to have sex with their respective wives with everything now going well.\n\n===''Great Grand Masti'' (2016)===\n{{Main article|Great Grand Masti}}\nThe film features three friends Amar, Meet and Prem who always want fun (Masti). The film begins with the title song where the three friends marry Sapna, Rekha and Nisha. They are unhappy with their marital lives because of their brother-in-law, sister-in-law, and mother-in-law. Amar's mother-in-law wants her late husband to be reborn and on the order of a fraud baba (fake spiritual leader) she has stopped her daughter from having any physical relations with Amar for over six months to achieve the rebirth of her late husband. Prem's sister-in-law is attractive but silly, she comes to live with them and wants to sleep with her elder sister, forcing Prem to sleep on the couch away from his wife. Meet's wife is a twin and whenever he tries to go near his wife, it turns on his brother-in-law (who is a body builder). The connection between the two twins causes great problems like Meet's wife beating him up unintentionally when her brother is beating some goon up.\n\nOne day they meet in a bar and decide to enjoy their lives. They decide to go to Amar's village to sell off his family haveli (old mansion) and meanwhile have fun with the beautiful ladies in the village. When they reach the village, they find out that people are scared of the haveli. An old man tells them that there used to be a father daughter duo who lived in the haveli 50 years ago, the daughter, Ragini was very beautiful and many boys were smitten by her beauty but her father never let any guy near her, at the age of 20, Ragini died due to snake bite but her soul still resides in the haveli in search of a man who'll do masti with her. \nThe guys laugh it off and proceed towards the haveli, there they meet a very attractive girl who's been living secretly in the haveli as she is alone and has no where to go. The boys hire her as their maid and each one starts trying to attract her. Soon it is revealed that she is indeed Ragini and she informs the boys that one of them must sleep with her in order to free her soul and whoever does so will die. The boys get scared and try escaping the mansion but to no avail. Prem commits to doing so in front of Ragini to buy them some time and meanwhile they hire Babu Rangeela, a male prostitute to sleep with Ragini. But on the last moment their wives show up and Ragini turns Babu into a chicken. Ragini makes the boys do weird stuff in front of their wives and in laws who join them at the haveli so they would leave. When the boys see that their wives are secretly fasting for them even when Ragini depicted them off as such perverts in front of them, they decide to confront Ragini. The meet Ragini and tell her they won't sleep with her and she can't harm them as their wives are fasting for their long lives. Ragini hurts them but they light fire around her and call her father's spirit to help them. Rather Babu's spirit comes (who was cooked by the three wives) and does Masti with Ragini hence satisfying her urge. Babu and Ragini leave the world together and the three couples live happily ever after.\n<ref>[http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/great-grand-masti-first-look-out-riteish-deshmukh-aftab-shivdasani-vivek-oberoi-starrer-set-to-triple-the-fun-2856005/ \"Great Grand Masti first look out, Riteish Deshmukh, Aftab Shivdasani, Vivek Oberoi starrer set to triple the fun\"]</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{| cla