{"title_page": "Grace Akallo", "text_new": "{{short description|Ugandan woman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{distinguish|Grace Akello}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix  = \n|name              = Grace Akallo\n|honorific_suffix  = \n|native_name       = \n|native_name_lang  = \n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|alt           = \n|caption       = \n|birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1981}} <!-- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{birth date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} if dead-->\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n|birth_place   = \n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = \n|placeofburial_label = \n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nickname      = \n|birth_name    = \n|allegiance    = [[Lord's Resistance Army]]\n|branch        = \n|serviceyears  = 1996\u201397\n|rank          = \n|servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n|unit          = \n|commands      = \n|battles       = \n|battles_label = \n|awards        =\n|spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> \n|relations     =\n|laterwork     = \n|signature     = \n|website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Grace Akallo''' (born 1981) is a [[Uganda]]n woman<ref name=Something>{{Cite web|publisher=[[Do Something]]|title=Fighting Worldwide Trafficking Through Documentary: A Review of Not My Life|url=http://www.dosomething.org/news/fighting-worldwide-trafficking-through-documentary-review-not-my-life|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref> who, at the age of 15,<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[China Radio International]]|title=Former Child Soldier Tells Her Story at UN Security Council|author=Lucy-Claire Saunders|date=30 April 2009|url=http://english.cri.cn/6966/2009/04/30/1361s480281.htm|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> was [[Aboke abductions|abducted]] by [[Joseph Kony]] to be used as a [[Military use of children|child soldier]]<ref name=Connecticut>{{Cite AV media|title=Human Trafficking: Modern Day Slavery|date=17 April 2013|publisher=[[Connecticut Public Radio]]|author=John Dankosky|url=http://www.yourpublicmedia.org/content/wnpr/human-trafficking-modern-day-slavery|accessdate=21 August 2013}}</ref> in the [[Lord's Resistance Army]] (LRA).<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Star Tribune]]|author=John Rash|title=Dehumanizing human trafficking on, off screen|date=3 August 2013|url=http://www.startribune.com/opinion/commentaries/218171341.html|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> At the time of her abduction, Akallo was attending [[St. Mary's College Kisubi|St. Mary's College]], a [[Catholic school|Catholic boarding school]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2012/04/19/kony-child-soldier|title=Former Kony Child Soldier Tells Her Story|date=19 April 2012|work=[[WBUR]]|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> in Kisubi, Uganda.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hynes|first=Patricia|date=2017|title=Girl Soldiers: Forgotten Casualties of War|url=|journal=Peace and Freedom; Philadelphia|volume=77|pages=4-5|via=ProQuest}}</ref> As part of her initiation into the army, she was forced to kill another girl, a very common practice among armies that employ child soldiers.<ref name=Connecticut/> Akallo remained in the LRA for seven months,<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Catholic News Service]] |title=Former teen soldier asks U.S. to help work for peace in Uganda |author=Agostino Bono |date=12 October 2006 |url=http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/0605809.htm |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20061017185846/http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/0605809.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 October 2006 |accessdate=2 September 2013 }}</ref> during which she became a skilled [[AK-47]] user.<ref name=Connecticut/> She was raped<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|title=Night vigil shines light on 'invisible children'|author=Debra Carlton Harrell|date=28 April 2006|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/Night-vigil-shines-light-on-invisible-children-1202294.php|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> and became a [[Sexual slavery|sexual slave]].<ref name=Something/> She was eventually rehabilitated and became a mother.<ref name=Connecticut/> \n\nThe 2007 book ''Girl Soldier: A Story of Hope for Northern Uganda's Children'' is a biography of Akallo written by Faith J.H. McDonnell.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]] |title=Adair: Speaking out about an African atrocity |author=Jeff Adair |date=24 February 2008 |url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/opinions/x1116892711 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130903050044/http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/opinions/x1116892711 |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 September 2013 |accessdate=2 September 2013 }}</ref> Akallo is interviewed in the 2011 documentary film ''[[Not My Life]]'' on the subject of [[human trafficking]], saying that \"this kind of evil must be stopped.\"<ref name=Root />\n\nAfter escaping the army, Grace returned to St. Mary's School<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=A Child's Hell in the Lord's Resistance Army|first=DeNeen L.|last=Brown|date=10 May 2006|work=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/05/09/AR2006050901907.html|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> to finish her high-school education. She began her college education at the [[Uganda Christian University]]. After giving a speech for [[Amnesty International]] in New York, she received a scholarship to finish her undergraduate degree at [[Gordon College (Massachusetts)|Gordon College]] in [[Massachusetts]]<ref name=\":0\" />. Grace majored in communications with a desire to continue studying international relations and conflict resolution. Grace went on to receive her master's degree from [[Clark University]]. She would use her information gained in her studies and experiences to try to keep what happened to her from happening to other innocent children. Grace used the experiences she had from being a child soldier to help counsel children who had escaped like her.\n\nGrace gave many speeches at educational establishments such as [[Rutgers University]] in New Jersey and [[Roosevelt University]] in Chicago. She also shared her story on shows including ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]''. Grace worked lobbying United States congressmen about the issue of [[child slavery]] in Uganda.<ref name=\"africanwomenrights.org\">{{cite web|title=What We Do|website= United Africans for Women & Children Rights|url=http://www.africanwomenrights.org/what_we_do/|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nGrace began her career as an advocate for peace and justice with jobs at Rachelle Rehabilitation Center and [[World Vision USA]]. Grace later worked as a Public Relations and Advocacy Intern in America,<ref>{{cite web|title=Who We Are|website= United Africans for Women & Children Rights|url=http://www.africanwomenrights.org/who_we_are/staff.php|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> writing press releases and documents for media use. She reported on conferences including The Interfaith Summit on Africa, and drafted amendments for the Senate bill on children affected by war.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nIn America she has started a non-profit organisation called United Africans for Women and Children's Rights ([http://www.africanwomenrights.org UAWCR]) that aims to end the prosecution of child soldiers.<ref name=\"africanwomenrights.org\"/> Grace Akallo has also catalysed action in Washington D.C. to help end the violence in Uganda; in addition she has appeared in public to raise awareness amongst the common people in addition to the politicians.<ref name=Root>{{Cite news|work=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|title=Documentary Exposes Modern-Day Slavery|author=Lynette Holloway|date=23 October 2011|url=http://www.theroot.com/buzz/not-my-life-heroes-and-villains|accessdate=1 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623055339/http://www.theroot.com/buzz/not-my-life-heroes-and-villains|archivedate=23 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She appears in the documentary film ''Grace, Milly, Lucy... Child Soldiers''.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[NPR]]|title='Grace, Milly, Lucy': Girls Forced into Conflict|date=22 June 2010|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=128010112|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akallo, Grace}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Child crime victim advocates]]\n[[Category:Child soldiers in Africa]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped children]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped Ugandan people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lord's Resistance Army]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse victim advocates]]\n[[Category:Ugandan human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Ugandan Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Ugandan soldiers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Ugandan women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ugandan women]]\n[[Category:Women soldiers]]\n[[Category:Uganda Christian University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ugandan woman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{distinguish|Grace Akello}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix  = \n|name              = Grace Akallo\n|honorific_suffix  = \n|native_name       = \n|native_name_lang  = \n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|alt           = \n|caption       = \n|birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1981}} <!-- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{birth date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} if dead-->\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n|birth_place   = \n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = \n|placeofburial_label = \n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nickname      = \n|birth_name    = \n|allegiance    = [[Lord's Resistance Army]]\n|branch        = \n|serviceyears  = 1996\u201397\n|rank          = \n|servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n|unit          = \n|commands      = \n|battles       = \n|battles_label = \n|awards        =\n|spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> \n|relations     =\n|laterwork     = \n|signature     = \n|website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Grace Akallo''' (born 1981) is a [[Uganda]]n woman<ref name=Something>{{Cite web|publisher=[[Do Something]]|title=Fighting Worldwide Trafficking Through Documentary: A Review of Not My Life|url=http://www.dosomething.org/news/fighting-worldwide-trafficking-through-documentary-review-not-my-life|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref> who, at the age of 15,<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[China Radio International]]|title=Former Child Soldier Tells Her Story at UN Security Council|author=Lucy-Claire Saunders|date=30 April 2009|url=http://english.cri.cn/6966/2009/04/30/1361s480281.htm|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> was [[Aboke abductions|abducted]] by [[Joseph Kony]] to be used as a [[Military use of children|child soldier]]<ref name=Connecticut>{{Cite AV media|title=Human Trafficking: Modern Day Slavery|date=17 April 2013|publisher=[[Connecticut Public Radio]]|author=John Dankosky|url=http://www.yourpublicmedia.org/content/wnpr/human-trafficking-modern-day-slavery|accessdate=21 August 2013}}</ref> in the [[Lord's Resistance Army]] (LRA).<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Star Tribune]]|author=John Rash|title=Dehumanizing human trafficking on, off screen|date=3 August 2013|url=http://www.startribune.com/opinion/commentaries/218171341.html|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> At the time of her abduction, Akallo was attending [[St. Mary's College Kisubi|St. Mary's College]], a [[Catholic school|Catholic boarding school]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2012/04/19/kony-child-soldier|title=Former Kony Child Soldier Tells Her Story|date=19 April 2012|work=[[WBUR]]|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> in Kisubi, Uganda.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hynes|first=Patricia|date=2017|title=Girl Soldiers: Forgotten Casualties of War|url=|journal=Peace and Freedom; Philadelphia|volume=77|pages=4-5|via=ProQuest}}</ref> As part of her initiation into the army, she was forced to kill another girl, a very common practice among armies that employ child soldiers.<ref name=Connecticut/> Akallo remained in the LRA for seven months,<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Catholic News Service]] |title=Former teen soldier asks U.S. to help work for peace in Uganda |author=Agostino Bono |date=12 October 2006 |url=http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/0605809.htm |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20061017185846/http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/0605809.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 October 2006 |accessdate=2 September 2013 }}</ref> during which she became a skilled [[AK-47]] user.<ref name=Connecticut/> She was raped<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|title=Night vigil shines light on 'invisible children'|author=Debra Carlton Harrell|date=28 April 2006|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/Night-vigil-shines-light-on-invisible-children-1202294.php|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> and became a [[Sexual slavery|sexual slave]].<ref name=Something/> She was eventually rehabilitated and became a mother.<ref name=Connecticut/> \n\nThe 2007 book ''Girl Soldier: A Story of Hope for Northern Uganda's Children'' is a biography of Akallo written by Faith J.H. McDonnell.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]] |title=Adair: Speaking out about an African atrocity |author=Jeff Adair |date=24 February 2008 |url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/opinions/x1116892711 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130903050044/http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/opinions/x1116892711 |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 September 2013 |accessdate=2 September 2013 }}</ref> Akallo is interviewed in the 2011 documentary film ''[[Not My Life]]'' on the subject of [[human trafficking]], saying that \"this kind of evil must be stopped.\"<ref name=Root />\n\nAfter escaping the army, Grace returned to St. Mary's School<ref>{{cite web|title=A Child's Hell in the Lord's Resistance Army|first=DeNeen L.|last=Brown|date=10 May 2006|work=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/05/09/AR2006050901907.html|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> to finish her high-school education. She began her college education at the [[Uganda Christian University]]. After giving a speech for [[Amnesty International]] in New York, she received a scholarship to finish her undergraduate degree at a college in [[Massachusetts]]. Grace majored in communications with a desire to continue studying international relations and conflict resolution. Grace went on to receive her master's degree from [[Clark University]]. She would use her information gained in her studies and experiences to try to keep what happened to her from happening to other innocent children. Grace used the experiences she had from being a child soldier to help counsel children who had escaped like her.\n\nGrace gave many speeches at educational establishments such as [[Rutgers University]] in New Jersey and [[Roosevelt University]] in Chicago. She also shared her story on shows including ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]''. Grace worked lobbying United States congressmen about the issue of [[child slavery]] in Uganda.<ref name=\"africanwomenrights.org\">{{cite web|title=What We Do|website= United Africans for Women & Children Rights|url=http://www.africanwomenrights.org/what_we_do/|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nGrace began her career as an advocate for peace and justice with jobs at Rachelle Rehabilitation Center and [[World Vision USA]]. Grace later worked as a Public Relations and Advocacy Intern in America,<ref>{{cite web|title=Who We Are|website= United Africans for Women & Children Rights|url=http://www.africanwomenrights.org/who_we_are/staff.php|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> writing press releases and documents for media use. She reported on conferences including The Interfaith Summit on Africa, and drafted amendments for the Senate bill on children affected by war.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nIn America she has started a non-profit organisation called United Africans for Women and Children's Rights ([http://www.africanwomenrights.org UAWCR]) that aims to end the prosecution of child soldiers.<ref name=\"africanwomenrights.org\"/> Grace Akallo has also catalysed action in Washington D.C. to help end the violence in Uganda; in addition she has appeared in public to raise awareness amongst the common people in addition to the politicians.<ref name=Root>{{Cite news|work=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|title=Documentary Exposes Modern-Day Slavery|author=Lynette Holloway|date=23 October 2011|url=http://www.theroot.com/buzz/not-my-life-heroes-and-villains|accessdate=1 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623055339/http://www.theroot.com/buzz/not-my-life-heroes-and-villains|archivedate=23 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She appears in the documentary film ''Grace, Milly, Lucy... Child Soldiers''.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[NPR]]|title='Grace, Milly, Lucy': Girls Forced into Conflict|date=22 June 2010|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=128010112|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akallo, Grace}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Child crime victim advocates]]\n[[Category:Child soldiers in Africa]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped children]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped Ugandan people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lord's Resistance Army]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse victim advocates]]\n[[Category:Ugandan human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Ugandan Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Ugandan soldiers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Ugandan women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ugandan women]]\n[[Category:Women soldiers]]\n[[Category:Uganda Christian University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "23hjt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added the name of the college Akallo attended and added a citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grace_Akallo"}
{"title_page": "A Quiet Place Part II", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 film directed by John Krasinski}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Quiet Place Part II\n| image          = A Quiet Place Part II theatrical poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[John Krasinski]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Bay]]\n* [[Andrew Form]]\n* [[Brad Fuller (producer)|Brad Fuller]]\n* John Krasinski\n}}\n| writer         = John Krasinski\n| based on       = {{Based on|Characters|[[Bryan Woods]]<ref name=\"evans20191218\" />|[[Scott Beck]]<ref name=\"evans20191218\" />}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Emily Blunt]]\n* [[Cillian Murphy]]\n* [[Millicent Simmonds]]\n* [[Noah Jupe]]\n* [[Djimon Hounsou]]\n* John Krasinski<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.aquietplacemovie.com/synopsis/ | title=A Quiet Place Part II: Synopsis | work=aquietplacemovie.com | publisher=[[Paramount Pictures]] | accessdate=February 14, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213201436/https://www.aquietplacemovie.com/synopsis/ | archive-date=February 13, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n| music          = [[Marco Beltrami]]\n| editing        = [[Michael P. Shawver]]\n| cinematography = [[Polly Morgan (cinematographer)|Polly Morgan]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Platinum Dunes]]<ref name=\"produc\">{{cite web |url=https://m.inquirer.net/inqpop/85022 |title=WATCH: Deadlier Threats Abound in the First Trailer of 'A Quiet Place Part II' |website=[[Inquirer.net]] |date=January 8, 2020 |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220182846/https://m.inquirer.net/inqpop/85022 |archive-date=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Sunday Night Productions]]<ref name=\"produc\" />\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|3|8|New York City|2020|9|4|United States}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[American Sign Language]]\n* English\n}}\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''A Quiet Place Part II''''' is a 2020 American [[horror film]] and sequel to ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'' (2018). The sequel film was written and directed by [[John Krasinski]] and stars [[Emily Blunt]], [[Millicent Simmonds]], and [[Noah Jupe]], reprising their roles from the first film. [[Cillian Murphy]] and [[Djimon Hounsou]] also joined the cast. Krasinski also reprises his role from the first film in newly-filmed flashback sequences.\n\n[[Paramount Pictures]], the studio behind the first film, began development of a sequel in April 2018 following the box office success of the first film. By the following August, Krasinski was writing the film, and he was hired in February 2019 to direct. Production took place in [[Western New York]] from June to September 2019.\n\nThe film had its world premiere in [[New York City]] on March 8, 2020. Paramount plans to release the film in theaters on {{nowrap|September 4}}, 2020. The studio initially planned to release the film in late March 2020 but postponed it due to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Synopsis==\n{{Quote|\"Following the deadly events at home, the Abbott family must now face the terrors of the outside world as they continue their fight for survival in silence. Forced to venture into the unknown, they quickly realize that the creatures that hunt by sound are not the only threats that lurk beyond the sand path.\"<ref name=\"evans20191218\" />|source=[[Paramount Pictures]]}}\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Emily Blunt]] as Evelyn Abbott\n*[[Cillian Murphy]] as Emmett. Murphy described his character Emmett, \"For me, Emmett represents where the heart of the world lies right now, which is: finally feeling like they've all given up. Here comes this girl [Regan] who allows you to believe in more, and allows you to believe in yourself. That idea, I've always been really enthralled by.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Briers | first=Michael | url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/a-quiet-place-part-ii-cillian-murphy/ | title=New ''A Quiet Place: Part II'' Photo Introduces Cillian Murphy's Stranger | work=We Got This Covered | date=January 13, 2020 | accessdate=January 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023701/https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/a-quiet-place-part-ii-cillian-murphy/ | archive-date=January 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Millicent Simmonds]] as Regan Abbott, Lee and Evelyn's deaf daughter and Marcus's sister. Simmonds described her character's evolution after the first film, \"She has a lot of pressure to become an adult very quickly.\" She has more of a leading role in the sequel, and according to ''[[Syfy Wire]]'', \"Deafness and ASL are inherently linked to the heroism of its heroine.\" Simmonds worked with an ASL coach to make sure her signing and articulation were clean. She said she felt \"a sense of pressure\" being in a position to represent the deaf and hard of hearing.<ref>{{cite news | last=Oller | first=Jacob | url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/a-quiet-place-part-2-emily-blunt | title=A Quiet Place Part II: Emily Blunt says the film rests on the shoulders of its younger cast | work=[[Syfy Wire]] | date=March 10, 2020 | accessdate=March 11, 2020 }}</ref>\n*[[Noah Jupe]] as Marcus Abbott, Lee and Evelyn's son and Regan's brother\n*[[Djimon Hounsou]]\n*[[John Krasinski]] as Lee Abbott, Evelyn's deceased husband and Regan and Marcus's father.<ref name=\"evans20200131\">{{cite news | last=Evans | first=Greg | url=https://deadline.com/video/quiet-place-part-ii-trailer-super-bowl-ad-john-krasinski-surprise/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Trailer: Super Bowl Spot Surprises From The Start | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=January 31, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131183645/https://deadline.com/video/quiet-place-part-ii-trailer-super-bowl-ad-john-krasinski-surprise/ | archive-date=January 31, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> He appears in newly-filmed flashback sequences depicting the days when the creatures first arrived. Krasinski said he wrote himself into the sequel because the first film \"was such a personal experience\" and his \"love letter\" to his children. He said, \"It was really important for me to continue the metaphor and we actually start dealing with how this all started.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Russell | first=Steve | url=https://www.cbr.com/a-quiet-place-why-john-krasinski-wrote-himself-back/ | title=A Quiet Place: Krasinski Reveals Why He Wrote Himself Back Into the Franchise | work=[[Comic Book Resources]] | date=February 12, 2020 | accessdate=February 16, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213162445/https://www.cbr.com/a-quiet-place-why-john-krasinski-wrote-himself-back/ | archive-date=February 13, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Development, writing, and casting===\n[[Paramount Pictures]] produced the first film, ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'', on a budget of {{nowrap|$17 million}}.<ref>{{cite magazine | last=McClintock | first=Pamela | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/a-quiet-place-screams-past-300m-at-global-box-office-1114103 | title=Box-Office Milestone: 'A Quiet Place' Screams Past $300M Globally | magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=May 22, 2018 | accessdate=December 18, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218193839/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/a-quiet-place-screams-past-300m-at-global-box-office-1114103 | archive-date=December 18, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Paramount released the film in the United States and Canada in April 2018 and grossed {{nowrap|$50.2 million}} on opening weekend, well above a mid-$20 million forecast. Later in April, Paramount Chair and CEO [[Jim Gianopulos]] announced that a sequel was in development. The first film ultimately grossed $188 million in the US and Canada and $340.9 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/best-movie-profit-2018-green-book-halloween-a-quiet-place-the-nun-crazy-rich-asians-1202589429/ | title=Small Movies, Big Profits: 2018 Most Valuable Blockbuster Tournament | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=April 8, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825021715/https://deadline.com/2019/04/best-movie-profit-2018-green-book-halloween-a-quiet-place-the-nun-crazy-rich-asians-1202589429/ | archive-date=August 25, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[John Krasinski]], who co-wrote, directed and starred in the first film, said he considered it \"as a one-off\".<ref name=\"blyth\">{{cite news | last=Blyth | first=Antonia | url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place-sequel-might-explore-1202384737/ | title=John Krasinski: 'A Quiet Place' Sequel Might Explore 'Who Was On The Other End Of Those Fires' | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=May 8, 2018 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122062824/https://deadline.com/2018/05/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place-sequel-might-explore-1202384737/ | archive-date=November 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Uncertain of finding similar success in a sequel, he initially told Paramount to seek another writer and director.<ref name=\"blyth\" /> The first film's screenwriters [[Scott Beck]] and [[Bryan Woods]] did not return for the sequel. Woods said they were not interested in a franchise approach and that they would rather try \"to create original ideas\" and use their writing credits \"as an opportunity to push several projects\".<ref>{{cite news | last=Scott | first=Ryan | url=https://movieweb.com/a-quiet-place-two-writers-scott-beck-bryan-woods/ | title=A Quiet Place Writers Explain Why They're Less Involved with the Sequel [Exclusive] | work=[[MovieWeb]] | date=September 11, 2019 | accessdate=January 14, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114164709/https://movieweb.com/a-quiet-place-two-writers-scott-beck-bryan-woods/ | archive-date=January 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Beck said, \"Instead of focusing on sequels per se, it's about investing back into the ecosystem of original ideas in a massive marketplace.\"<ref>{{cite magazine | last=Crump | first=Andy | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/haunt-writers-quiet-place-success-crazy-next-movie-1239164 | title='Haunt' Writers on Their 'A Quiet Place' Success and the 'Crazy, Zany' Script They're Working On | magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=September 13, 2019 | accessdate=January 14, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114164711/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/haunt-writers-quiet-place-success-crazy-next-movie-1239164 | archive-date=January 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThree months after ''A Quiet Place''{{'}}s release, Krasinski decided to brainstorm ideas for a sequel.<ref name=\"rubin\" /> According to Krasinski, Paramount rejected pitches from other writers and directors that were considered too franchise-oriented.<ref name=\"buchanan\">{{cite news | last=Buchanan | first=Kyle | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/03/movies/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place.html | title='A Quiet Place' Was a Huge Hit. Will Oscar Listen? | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 3, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122015221/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/03/movies/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place.html | archive-date=November 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> He said, \"I had this small idea, which was to make Millie [Simmonds] the lead of the movie... her character opens the door to all the themes I was dealing with in the first movie.\"<ref name=\"rubin\">{{cite magazine | last=Rubin | first=Rebecca | url=https://variety.com/2020/scene/news/quiet-place-2-premiere-john-krasinski-emily-blunt-1203527522/ | title=How John Krasinski Convinced Emily Blunt to Star in 'A Quiet Place 2' | magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 10, 2020 }}</ref> The studio invited him to write a script based on his idea.<ref name=\"buchanan\" /> By August 2018, Krasinski was writing the film.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/top-gun-2-a-quiet-place-2-new-release-date-1202446275/ | title='Top Gun: Maverick' Flies To Summer 2020 With 'A Quiet Place' Sequel & More: Paramount Release Date Changes | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 29, 2018 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829234505/https://deadline.com/2018/08/top-gun-2-a-quiet-place-2-new-release-date-1202446275/ | archive-date=August 29, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> In the following February, he was hired to direct the sequel, and actors [[Emily Blunt]], [[Millicent Simmonds]], and [[Noah Jupe]] were confirmed to reprise their roles.<ref>{{cite news | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/emily-blunt-millicent-simmonds-noah-jupe-return-a-quiet-place-2-1189124 | title='A Quiet Place 2': Emily Blunt, Millicent Simmonds, Noah Jupe in Talks to Return (Exclusive) | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=February 22, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223034956/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/emily-blunt-millicent-simmonds-noah-jupe-return-a-quiet-place-2-1189124 | archive-date=February 23, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In March, [[Cillian Murphy]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite news | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/cillian-murphy-talks-join-a-quiet-place-sequel-1198028 | title=Cillian Murphy in Talks to Join Emily Blunt in 'A Quiet Place' Sequel (Exclusive) | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=March 29, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429025531/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/cillian-murphy-talks-join-a-quiet-place-sequel-1198028 | archive-date=April 29, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In the following June, [[Brian Tyree Henry]] joined the cast,<ref>{{cite news | last1=Verhoeven | first1=Beatrice | last2=Gonzalez | first2=Umberto | url=https://www.thewrap.com/brian-tyree-henry-in-talks-to-join-emily-blunt-in-a-quiet-place-2-exclusive/ | title=Brian Tyree Henry in Talks to Join Emily Blunt in 'A Quiet Place 2' (Exclusive) | work=[[TheWrap]] | date=June 5, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606001451/https://www.thewrap.com/brian-tyree-henry-in-talks-to-join-emily-blunt-in-a-quiet-place-2-exclusive/ | archive-date=June 6, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> but he left the film due to scheduling problems. He was replaced by [[Djimon Hounsou]] in August.<ref>{{cite news | last=Fleming Jr. | first=Mike | url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/djimon-hounsou-to-replace-brian-tyree-henry-in-starring-role-in-a-quiet-place-2-1202666289/ | title=Djimon Hounsou Steps Into 'A Quiet Place Part II;' Brian Tyree Henry Exits Over Scheduling | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 12, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914082539/https://deadline.com/2019/08/djimon-hounsou-to-replace-brian-tyree-henry-in-starring-role-in-a-quiet-place-2-1202666289/ | archive-date=September 14, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nIn June, production began on the sequel.<ref>{{cite news | last=Ames | first=Jeff | url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1077169-a-quiet-place-2-sneaks-into-production | title=A Quiet Place 2 Sneaks Into Production | work=[[ComingSoon.net]] | date=June 20, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621024054/https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1077169-a-quiet-place-2-sneaks-into-production | archive-date=June 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Filming officially commenced on {{nowrap|July 15}}, 2019.<ref>{{cite news | last=Collis | first=Clark | url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/07/15/a-quiet-place-2-starts-shooting-john-krasinski/ | title=John Krasinski announces ''A Quiet Place 2'' has started shooting | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=July 15, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016040850/https://ew.com/movies/2019/07/15/a-quiet-place-2-starts-shooting-john-krasinski/ | archive-date=October 16, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> There were 47 days of filming throughout [[Western New York]], including locations like [[Akron, New York|Akron]], [[Olcott, New York|Olcott]], [[Dunkirk, New York|Dunkirk]], [[Lackawanna, New York|Lackawanna]], and [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Staff | url=http://www.filmbuffaloniagara.com/latest-news/filmed-in-wny-a-quiet-place-part-ii-hits-theaters-this-march/ | title=Filmed in WNY&nbsp;\u2013 A Quiet Place Part II Hits Theaters This March | work=Buffalo Niagara Film Commission | accessdate=March 3, 2020 }}</ref> Other locations included [[Erie County, New York|Erie County]] and the city of [[North Tonawanda, New York|North Tonawanda]],<ref>{{cite news | last=WIVB Staff | url=https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/niagara-county/north-tonawanda/a-quiet-place-2-looking-to-film-in-north-tonawanda/ | title='A Quiet Place 2' looking to film in North Tonawanda | work=[[WIVB-TV]] | date=August 2, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219212831/https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/niagara-county/north-tonawanda/a-quiet-place-2-looking-to-film-in-north-tonawanda/ | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> and Barcelona Harbor in the town of [[Westfield, New York|Westfield]] in [[Chautauqua County, New York|Chautauqua County]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Tichy | first=Eric | url=https://www.observertoday.com/news/page-one/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-lands-at-barcelona/ | title='A Quiet Place 2' lands at Barcelona | work=Observer Today | publisher=[[Ogden Newspapers]] | date=August 9, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810135958/https://www.observertoday.com/news/page-one/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-lands-at-barcelona/ | archive-date=August 10, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Filming also took place on a [[sound stage]] in Buffalo. One of the last filming locations, the northbound [[South Grand Island Bridge]], was shut down for 13 hours for filming.<ref>{{cite news | last=Besecker | first=Aaron | url=https://buffalonews.com/2019/08/19/a-quiet-place-2-filming-to-close-grand-island-bridge-for-13-hours/ | title='A Quiet Place 2' filming to close Grand Island bridge for 13 hours | work=[[The Buffalo News]] | date=August 19, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915160236/https://buffalonews.com/2019/08/19/a-quiet-place-2-filming-to-close-grand-island-bridge-for-13-hours/ | archive-date=September 15, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Western New York, filming took place in the NY region of [[Hudson Valley]], specifically the towns of [[Dover, New York|Dover]], [[Pawling (town), New York|Pawling]], and [[New Paltz, New York|New Paltz]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Barry | first=John W. | url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/2020/04/03/coronavirus-a-quiet-place-part-ii-john-krasinski-emily-blunt-paramount-pictures/2938691001/ | title=Coronavirus: 'A Quiet Place Part II' now set for Sept. 4 release in theaters | work=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]] | date=April 3, 2020 | accessdate=April 3, 2020 }}\n*{{cite news | last=Barry | first=John W. | url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/09/13/john-krasinskis-a-quiet-place-sequel-close-road-production/2309956001/ | title=John Krasinski's 'A Quiet Place' sequel to close road for production | work=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]] | date=September 13, 2019 | accessdate=April 3, 2020 }}</ref> In New Paltz, the [[Wallkill Valley Rail Trail]] was revisited to film on a bridge that featured in the first film.<ref>{{cite news | last=Wilson | first=Geoffrey | url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/entertainment/movies/2019/09/19/a-quiet-place-sequel-film-crew-returns-new-paltz-bridge/2375770001/ | title='A Quiet Place' sequel: Film crew returns to New Paltz bridge featured in original movie | work=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]] | date=September 19, 2019 | accessdate=April 3, 2020 }}</ref> The production invested over $10 million in [[Upstate New York]], created 400 hires, and involved 300 background actors.<ref>{{cite news | last=Herbert | first=Geoff | url=https://www.newyorkupstate.com/entertainment/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-continues-filming-in-western-ny-marvel-star-joins-cast.html | title='A Quiet Place 2' continues filming in Western NY; Marvel star joins cast | work=[[The Post-Standard]] | date=August 14, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814153334/https://www.newyorkupstate.com/entertainment/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-continues-filming-in-western-ny-marvel-star-joins-cast.html | archive-date=August 14, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> By late September, production was finished.<ref>{{cite news | last=Hermanns | first=Grant | url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1101485-a-quiet-place-part-ii-wraps-production | title=A Quiet Place Part II Wraps Production! | work=[[ComingSoon.net]] | date=September 25, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Sound design===\nFor the sequel's sound design, supervising sound editors [[Erik Aadahl]] and [[Ethan Van der Ryn]] and [[re-recording mixer]] [[Brandon Proctor]] reprised their roles. Krasinski instructed them to try to \"follow the rules\" set up in the first film and said of the experience, \"What we found was by doing that, and not trying to be cool, we ended up uncovering way more stuff than we ever would've been able to [otherwise].\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Oller | first=Jacob | url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/quiet-place-part-ii-sound-design-follow-the-rules | title=John Krasinski's one rule for A Quiet Place Part II's sound design: 'Just follow the rules' | work=[[Syfy Wire]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 10, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n\nParamount Pictures previewed a 30-second teaser trailer for ''A Quiet Place Part II'' before select theatrical screenings of ''[[Black Christmas (2019 film)|Black Christmas]]'', which was released on December 13, 2019. Less than a week later, the teaser trailer became available online. A full trailer was released on January 1, 2020.<ref name=\"evans20191218\" /> During pre-game coverage before the [[Super Bowl LIV]] on February 2, 2020, Paramount released a 30-second TV spot,<ref name=\"evans20200131\" /> which revealed that Krasinski reprised his role in a newly-filmed flashback sequence.<ref>{{cite news | last=Chitwood | first=Adam | url=https://collider.com/a-quiet-place-2-super-bowl-2020-ad-trailer/ | title='A Quiet Place: Part II' Super Bowl Ad Has a Big Surprise | work=[[Collider.com]] | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201131147/https://collider.com/a-quiet-place-2-super-bowl-2020-ad-trailer/ | archive-date=February 1, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March, Paramount initiated \"survival room\" experiences in New York and Los Angeles in which groups of visitors can try to overcome \"physical and mental obstacles\" without making too much noise.<ref>{{cite news | last=Rosenberg | first=Adam | url=https://mashable.com/article/quiet-place-2-survival-rooms-poster-trailer/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Survival Rooms invite fans to live the horror for themselves | work=[[Mashable]] | date=February 25, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 }}</ref> The setups cost less than a million dollars for Paramount. A marketing executive anticipated between seven thousand and eight thousand people to go through the experiences and for fans and [[social media influencer]]s to engage in [[experiential marketing]].<ref>{{cite magazine | last=Handy | first=Bruce | url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/16/shhhhh-choosing-to-be-very-afraid | title=Shhh! Choosing to Be Very Afraid | magazine=[[The New Yorker]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 9, 2020 }}</ref> [[Emily Blunt]] appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' on March 10 to promote the film. She appeared in a parody commercial advertising ''A Quiet Plane'', starring as a stewardess that enforces silence as a top priority to a plane's passengers.<ref>{{cite news | last=Jackson | first=Matthew | url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/emily-blunt-a-quiet-place-part-ii-spoof | title=Emily Blunt creates world's quietest airline in A Quiet Place late night spoof | work=[[Syfy Wire]] | date=March 11, 2020 | accessdate=March 11, 2020 }}</ref> Before the film's postponement ([[#Release|see below]]), Paramount planned to host a [[double feature|double-feature]] event that screened the first and second films with collectors prints provided to attendees.<ref>{{cite news | last=Perez | first=Chris | url=https://www.cbr.com/paramount-a-quiet-place-parts-i-ii-event/ | title=Paramount Announces A Quiet Place Parts I and II Double Feature Event | work=[[Comic Book Resources]] | date=February 29, 2020 | accessdate=March 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Box office forecast==\nIn January 2020, ''[[BoxOffice (magazine)|BoxOffice]]'' predicted the film would gross {{nowrap|$72 million}} in its initially-announced opening weekend in late March 2020. (The film was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].) It based the forecast on the first film's success on its own opening weekend ({{nowrap|$50.2 million}}) and in the long run, the sequel's early social metrics being strong, and the continued involvement of Emily Blunt and John Krasinski. The site also noted that the film would face competition from the likes of ''[[Mulan (2020 film)|Mulan]]''.<ref>{{cite news | last=Robbins | first=Shawn | url=https://www.boxofficepro.com/long-range-box-office-tracking-a-quiet-place-part-ii/ | title=Long Range Box Office Tracking: ''A Quiet Place Part II'' | work=[[BoxOffice (magazine)|BoxOffice]] | date=January 24, 2020 | accessdate=January 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127141420/https://www.boxofficepro.com/long-range-box-office-tracking-a-quiet-place-part-ii/ | archive-date=January 27, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"pallotta\" /> In February, early industry tracking had the film debuting to around $55-60 million.<ref name=\"d'alessandro\" /><ref>{{cite magazine | last=Rubin | first=Rebecca | url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/box-office-a-quiet-place-2-early-tracking-1203517739/ | title=Box Office: 'A Quiet Place 2' Tracking for $55 Million-Plus Debut | magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 28, 2020 }}</ref> Analysts compared the debut to those of recent films ''[[Us (2019 film)|Us]]'', ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'', ''[[Halloween (2018 film)|Halloween]]'', and ''[[It Chapter Two]]''. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]''{{'}}s Anthony D'Alessandro wrote, \"''A Quiet Place Part II'' is currently strong with females under 25, African Americans and Hispanic demos, but overall I hear it's strong with all quads.\"<ref name=\"d'alessandro\">{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url= https://deadline.com/2020/02/a-quiet-place-part-ii-to-scare-up-60m-opening-early-box-office-forecast-1202869747/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' To Scare Up $60M Opening&nbsp;\u2013 Early Box Office Forecast | date=February 27, 2020 | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n''A Quiet Place Part II'' had its world premiere at the [[Lincoln Center]] in [[New York City]] on {{nowrap|March 8}}, 2020.<ref>{{cite news | last=Martin | first=Annie | url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/Movies/2020/03/09/John-Krasinski-praises-Emily-Blunt-at-A-Quiet-Place-2-premiere/6121583758813/ | title=John Krasinski praises Emily Blunt at 'A Quiet Place 2' premiere | work=[[United Press International]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 9, 2020 }}</ref> [[Paramount Pictures]] plans to release the film in theaters on {{nowrap|September 4}}, 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/a-quiet-place-part-ii-sets-new-september-2020-release-date-1287096|title='A Quiet Place Part II' Sets New September Release Date|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> after it postponed a March 2020 release due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite magazine | last=McClintock | first=Pamela | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/a-quiet-place-part-ii-sets-new-september-2020-release-date-1287096 | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Sets New September Release Date | magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=April 2, 2020 | accessdate=April 2, 2020 }}</ref> The September release date, announced on {{nowrap|April 2}}, is the start of the US holiday weekend [[Labor Day Weekend]]. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' wrote the weekend is \"summer [box office's] finale\" and \"typically the deadest period ever for moviegoing\" but that the studio anticipated pent-up demand after pandemic fears subside.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/top-gun-maverick-flies-to-christmas-corridor-spongebob-eyes-late-summer-quiet-place-ii-to-debut-labor-day-1202898738/ | title='Top Gun Maverick' Flies To Christmas Corridor, 'SpongeBob' Eyes Late Summer, 'Quiet Place II\u2019 To Debut Labor Day | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=April 2, 2020 | accessdate=April 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe studio initially planned to release the film in theaters globally starting on March 18, 2020 before it delayed the film's release due to the pandemic. Director John Krasinski said he wanted moviegoers to see the film together and that with the pandemic, it was not the right time to provide that experience.<ref name=\"grater\">{{cite news | last=Grater | first=Tom | url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/a-quiet-place-ii-delayed-coronavirus-crisis-1202880784/ | title='A Quiet Place II' Global Release Delayed To Avoid Coronavirus Crisis&nbsp;\u2013 Update | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=March 12, 2020 | accessdate=March 12, 2020 }}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' said that according to sources, Paramount spent around 60% of its budget for global prints and advertising. The periodical wrote that the film's delay was \"truly a shocker\" because the P&A expense seemed to indicate that rescheduling was not an option.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/mulan-new-mutants-antlers-moved-coronavirus-1202881355/ | title='Mulan', 'New Mutants' & 'Antlers' Moved By Disney As Coronavirus Grips Release Schedule | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=March 12, 2020 | accessdate=March 13, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe film was initially to be released in the United Kingdom and Australia on March 19, 2020,<ref>{{cite news | last=Bisset | first=Jennifer | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/a-quiet-place-2-first-reactions-slink-in/ | title=A Quiet Place 2 first reactions slink in: 'A masterclass in suspense' | work=[[CNET]] | date=March 5, 2020 | accessdate=March 6, 2020 }}</ref> and in the United States and Canada, including [[Dolby Cinema]] and [[IMAX]], on March 20, 2020.<ref name=\"evans20191218\">{{cite news | last=Evans | first=Greg | url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/a-quiet-place-part-ii-teaser-poster-release-emily-blunt-john-krasinski-1202812560/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Teaser Finally Making Noise Outside Sneak Peek Screenings | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=December 18, 2019 | accessdate=December 18, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218152102/https://deadline.com/2019/12/a-quiet-place-part-ii-teaser-poster-release-emily-blunt-john-krasinski-1202812560/ | archive-date=December 18, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Paramount initially stated on March 6 that it would not reschedule the film in response to the pandemic,<ref name=\"pallotta\">{{cite news | last=Pallotta | first=Frank | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/media/coronavirus-james-bond-box-office/index.html | title='No Time to Die' was the first major film to delay its release due to coronavirus. It may not be the last | work=[[CNN]] | date=March 6, 2020 | accessdate=March 9, 2020 }}</ref> but on March 12, the studio pulled the film from release worldwide with the intent of scheduling it later in the year.<ref name=\"grater\" />\n\nProducer [[Brad Fuller (producer)|Brad Fuller]] said for the film's US release, Paramount sought to maintain a [[PG-13]] rating (parental guidance suggested) like its predecessor and to avoid an R rating (restricted audiences) to appeal to a broad audience, including those who are offput by blood in R-rated horror films.<ref>{{cite news | last=Mobley | first=Joshua | url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/a-quiet-place-part-2-how-they-kept-the-gimmick-sca/1100-6474288/ | title=A Quiet Place Part 2: How They Kept The Gimmick Scary For The Sequel | work=[[GameSpot]] | date=March 11, 2020 | accessdate=March 11, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n*[[List of films featuring the deaf and hard of hearing]]\n*[[The Silence (2019 film)|The Silence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.aquietplacemovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt8332922}}\n\n{{Films directed by John Krasinski}}\n{{Platinum Dunes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quiet Place Part II, A}}\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:2020s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American monster movies]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American Sign Language films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about deaf people]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Krasinski]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Andrew Form]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Bradley Fuller]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael Bay]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Platinum Dunes films]]\n[[Category:Sequel films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 film directed by John Krasinski}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Quiet Place Part II\n| image          = A Quiet Place Part II theatrical poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[John Krasinski]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Bay]]\n* [[Andrew Form]]\n* [[Brad Fuller (producer)|Brad Fuller]]\n* John Krasinski\n}}\n| writer         = John Krasinski\n| based on       = {{Based on|Characters|[[Bryan Woods]]<ref name=\"evans20191218\" />|[[Scott Beck]]<ref name=\"evans20191218\" />}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Emily Blunt]]\n* [[Cillian Murphy]]\n* [[Millicent Simmonds]]\n* [[Noah Jupe]]\n* [[Djimon Hounsou]]\n* John Krasinski<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.aquietplacemovie.com/synopsis/ | title=A Quiet Place Part II: Synopsis | work=aquietplacemovie.com | publisher=[[Paramount Pictures]] | accessdate=February 14, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213201436/https://www.aquietplacemovie.com/synopsis/ | archive-date=February 13, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n| music          = [[Marco Beltrami]]\n| editing        = [[Michael P. Shawver]]\n| cinematography = [[Polly Morgan (cinematographer)|Polly Morgan]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Platinum Dunes]]<ref name=\"produc\">{{cite web |url=https://m.inquirer.net/inqpop/85022 |title=WATCH: Deadlier Threats Abound in the First Trailer of 'A Quiet Place Part II' |website=[[Inquirer.net]] |date=January 8, 2020 |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220182846/https://m.inquirer.net/inqpop/85022 |archive-date=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Sunday Night Productions]]<ref name=\"produc\" />\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|3|8|New York City|2020|9|4|United States}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[American Sign Language]]\n* English\n}}\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''A Quiet Place Part II''''' is a 2020 American [[horror film]] and sequel to ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'' (2018). The sequel film was written and directed by [[John Krasinski]] and stars [[Emily Blunt]], [[Millicent Simmonds]], and [[Noah Jupe]], reprising their roles from the first film. [[Cillian Murphy]] and [[Djimon Hounsou]] also joined the cast. Krasinski also reprises his role from the first film in newly-filmed flashback sequences.\n\n[[Paramount Pictures]], the studio behind the first film, began development of a sequel in April 2018 following the box office success of the first film. By the following August, Krasinski was writing the film, and he was hired in February 2019 to direct. Production took place in [[Western New York]] from June to September 2019.\n\nThe film had its world premiere in [[New York City]] on March 8, 2020. Paramount plans to release the film in theaters on {{nowrap|September 4}}, 2020. The studio initially planned to release the film in late March 2020 but postponed it due to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Synopsis==\n{{Quote|\"Following the deadly events at home, the Abbott family must now face the terrors of the outside world as they continue their fight for survival in silence. Forced to venture into the unknown, they quickly realize that the creatures that hunt by sound are not the only threats that lurk beyond the sand path.\"<ref name=\"evans20191218\" />|source=[[Paramount Pictures]]}}\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Emily Blunt]] as Evelyn Abbott\n*[[Cillian Murphy]] as Emmett. Murphy described his character Emmett, \"For me, Emmett represents where the heart of the world lies right now, which is: finally feeling like they've all given up. Here comes this girl [Regan] who allows you to believe in more, and allows you to believe in yourself. That idea, I've always been really enthralled by.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Briers | first=Michael | url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/a-quiet-place-part-ii-cillian-murphy/ | title=New ''A Quiet Place: Part II'' Photo Introduces Cillian Murphy's Stranger | work=We Got This Covered | date=January 13, 2020 | accessdate=January 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023701/https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/a-quiet-place-part-ii-cillian-murphy/ | archive-date=January 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Millicent Simmonds]] as Regan Abbott, Lee and Evelyn's deaf daughter and Marcus's sister. Simmonds described her character's evolution after the first film, \"She has a lot of pressure to become an adult very quickly.\" She has more of a leading role in the sequel, and according to ''[[Syfy Wire]]'', \"Deafness and ASL are inherently linked to the heroism of its heroine.\" Simmonds worked with an ASL coach to make sure her signing and articulation were clean. She said she felt \"a sense of pressure\" being in a position to represent the deaf and hard of hearing.<ref>{{cite news | last=Oller | first=Jacob | url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/a-quiet-place-part-2-emily-blunt | title=A Quiet Place Part II: Emily Blunt says the film rests on the shoulders of its younger cast | work=[[Syfy Wire]] | date=March 10, 2020 | accessdate=March 11, 2020 }}</ref>\n*[[Noah Jupe]] as Marcus Abbott, Lee and Evelyn's son and Regan's brother\n*[[Djimon Hounsou]]\n*[[John Krasinski]] as Lee Abbott, Evelyn's deceased husband and Regan and Marcus's father.<ref name=\"evans20200131\">{{cite news | last=Evans | first=Greg | url=https://deadline.com/video/quiet-place-part-ii-trailer-super-bowl-ad-john-krasinski-surprise/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Trailer: Super Bowl Spot Surprises From The Start | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=January 31, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131183645/https://deadline.com/video/quiet-place-part-ii-trailer-super-bowl-ad-john-krasinski-surprise/ | archive-date=January 31, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> He appears in newly-filmed flashback sequences depicting the days when the creatures first arrived. Krasinski said he wrote himself into the sequel because the first film \"was such a personal experience\" and his \"love letter\" to his children. He said, \"It was really important for me to continue the metaphor and we actually start dealing with how this all started.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Russell | first=Steve | url=https://www.cbr.com/a-quiet-place-why-john-krasinski-wrote-himself-back/ | title=A Quiet Place: Krasinski Reveals Why He Wrote Himself Back Into the Franchise | work=[[Comic Book Resources]] | date=February 12, 2020 | accessdate=February 16, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213162445/https://www.cbr.com/a-quiet-place-why-john-krasinski-wrote-himself-back/ | archive-date=February 13, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Development, writing, and casting===\n[[Paramount Pictures]] produced the first film, ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'', on a budget of {{nowrap|$17 million}}.<ref>{{cite magazine | last=McClintock | first=Pamela | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/a-quiet-place-screams-past-300m-at-global-box-office-1114103 | title=Box-Office Milestone: 'A Quiet Place' Screams Past $300M Globally | magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=May 22, 2018 | accessdate=December 18, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218193839/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/a-quiet-place-screams-past-300m-at-global-box-office-1114103 | archive-date=December 18, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Paramount released the film in the United States and Canada in April 2018 and grossed {{nowrap|$50.2 million}} on opening weekend, well above a mid-$20 million forecast. Later in April, Paramount Chair and CEO [[Jim Gianopulos]] announced that a sequel was in development. The first film ultimately grossed $188 million in the US and Canada and $340.9 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/best-movie-profit-2018-green-book-halloween-a-quiet-place-the-nun-crazy-rich-asians-1202589429/ | title=Small Movies, Big Profits: 2018 Most Valuable Blockbuster Tournament | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=April 8, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825021715/https://deadline.com/2019/04/best-movie-profit-2018-green-book-halloween-a-quiet-place-the-nun-crazy-rich-asians-1202589429/ | archive-date=August 25, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[John Krasinski]], who co-wrote, directed and starred in the first film, said he considered it \"as a one-off\".<ref name=\"blyth\">{{cite news | last=Blyth | first=Antonia | url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place-sequel-might-explore-1202384737/ | title=John Krasinski: 'A Quiet Place' Sequel Might Explore 'Who Was On The Other End Of Those Fires' | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=May 8, 2018 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122062824/https://deadline.com/2018/05/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place-sequel-might-explore-1202384737/ | archive-date=November 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Uncertain of finding similar success in a sequel, he initially told Paramount to seek another writer and director.<ref name=\"blyth\" /> The first film's screenwriters [[Scott Beck]] and [[Bryan Woods]] did not return for the sequel. Woods said they were not interested in a franchise approach and that they would rather try \"to create original ideas\" and use their writing credits \"as an opportunity to push several projects\".<ref>{{cite news | last=Scott | first=Ryan | url=https://movieweb.com/a-quiet-place-two-writers-scott-beck-bryan-woods/ | title=A Quiet Place Writers Explain Why They're Less Involved with the Sequel [Exclusive] | work=[[MovieWeb]] | date=September 11, 2019 | accessdate=January 14, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114164709/https://movieweb.com/a-quiet-place-two-writers-scott-beck-bryan-woods/ | archive-date=January 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Beck said, \"Instead of focusing on sequels per se, it's about investing back into the ecosystem of original ideas in a massive marketplace.\"<ref>{{cite magazine | last=Crump | first=Andy | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/haunt-writers-quiet-place-success-crazy-next-movie-1239164 | title='Haunt' Writers on Their 'A Quiet Place' Success and the 'Crazy, Zany' Script They're Working On | magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=September 13, 2019 | accessdate=January 14, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114164711/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/haunt-writers-quiet-place-success-crazy-next-movie-1239164 | archive-date=January 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThree months after ''A Quiet Place''{{'}}s release, Krasinski decided to brainstorm ideas for a sequel.<ref name=\"rubin\" /> According to Krasinski, Paramount rejected pitches from other writers and directors that were considered too franchise-oriented.<ref name=\"buchanan\">{{cite news | last=Buchanan | first=Kyle | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/03/movies/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place.html | title='A Quiet Place' Was a Huge Hit. Will Oscar Listen? | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 3, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122015221/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/03/movies/john-krasinski-a-quiet-place.html | archive-date=November 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> He said, \"I had this small idea, which was to make Millie [Simmonds] the lead of the movie... her character opens the door to all the themes I was dealing with in the first movie.\"<ref name=\"rubin\">{{cite magazine | last=Rubin | first=Rebecca | url=https://variety.com/2020/scene/news/quiet-place-2-premiere-john-krasinski-emily-blunt-1203527522/ | title=How John Krasinski Convinced Emily Blunt to Star in 'A Quiet Place 2' | magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 10, 2020 }}</ref> The studio invited him to write a script based on his idea.<ref name=\"buchanan\" /> By August 2018, Krasinski was writing the film.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/top-gun-2-a-quiet-place-2-new-release-date-1202446275/ | title='Top Gun: Maverick' Flies To Summer 2020 With 'A Quiet Place' Sequel & More: Paramount Release Date Changes | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 29, 2018 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829234505/https://deadline.com/2018/08/top-gun-2-a-quiet-place-2-new-release-date-1202446275/ | archive-date=August 29, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> In the following February, he was hired to direct the sequel, and actors [[Emily Blunt]], [[Millicent Simmonds]], and [[Noah Jupe]] were confirmed to reprise their roles.<ref>{{cite news | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/emily-blunt-millicent-simmonds-noah-jupe-return-a-quiet-place-2-1189124 | title='A Quiet Place 2': Emily Blunt, Millicent Simmonds, Noah Jupe in Talks to Return (Exclusive) | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=February 22, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223034956/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/emily-blunt-millicent-simmonds-noah-jupe-return-a-quiet-place-2-1189124 | archive-date=February 23, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In March, [[Cillian Murphy]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite news | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/cillian-murphy-talks-join-a-quiet-place-sequel-1198028 | title=Cillian Murphy in Talks to Join Emily Blunt in 'A Quiet Place' Sequel (Exclusive) | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=March 29, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429025531/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/cillian-murphy-talks-join-a-quiet-place-sequel-1198028 | archive-date=April 29, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In the following June, [[Brian Tyree Henry]] joined the cast,<ref>{{cite news | last1=Verhoeven | first1=Beatrice | last2=Gonzalez | first2=Umberto | url=https://www.thewrap.com/brian-tyree-henry-in-talks-to-join-emily-blunt-in-a-quiet-place-2-exclusive/ | title=Brian Tyree Henry in Talks to Join Emily Blunt in 'A Quiet Place 2' (Exclusive) | work=[[TheWrap]] | date=June 5, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606001451/https://www.thewrap.com/brian-tyree-henry-in-talks-to-join-emily-blunt-in-a-quiet-place-2-exclusive/ | archive-date=June 6, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> but he left the film due to scheduling problems. He was replaced by [[Djimon Hounsou]] in August.<ref>{{cite news | last=Fleming Jr. | first=Mike | url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/djimon-hounsou-to-replace-brian-tyree-henry-in-starring-role-in-a-quiet-place-2-1202666289/ | title=Djimon Hounsou Steps Into 'A Quiet Place Part II;' Brian Tyree Henry Exits Over Scheduling | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 12, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914082539/https://deadline.com/2019/08/djimon-hounsou-to-replace-brian-tyree-henry-in-starring-role-in-a-quiet-place-2-1202666289/ | archive-date=September 14, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nIn June, production began on the sequel.<ref>{{cite news | last=Ames | first=Jeff | url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1077169-a-quiet-place-2-sneaks-into-production | title=A Quiet Place 2 Sneaks Into Production | work=[[ComingSoon.net]] | date=June 20, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621024054/https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1077169-a-quiet-place-2-sneaks-into-production | archive-date=June 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Filming officially commenced on {{nowrap|July 15}}, 2019.<ref>{{cite news | last=Collis | first=Clark | url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/07/15/a-quiet-place-2-starts-shooting-john-krasinski/ | title=John Krasinski announces ''A Quiet Place 2'' has started shooting | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=July 15, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016040850/https://ew.com/movies/2019/07/15/a-quiet-place-2-starts-shooting-john-krasinski/ | archive-date=October 16, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> There were 47 days of filming throughout [[Western New York]], including locations like [[Akron, New York|Akron]], [[Olcott, New York|Olcott]], [[Dunkirk, New York|Dunkirk]], [[Lackawanna, New York|Lackawanna]], and [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Staff | url=http://www.filmbuffaloniagara.com/latest-news/filmed-in-wny-a-quiet-place-part-ii-hits-theaters-this-march/ | title=Filmed in WNY&nbsp;\u2013 A Quiet Place Part II Hits Theaters This March | work=Buffalo Niagara Film Commission | accessdate=March 3, 2020 }}</ref> Other locations included [[Erie County, New York|Erie County]] and the city of [[North Tonawanda, New York|North Tonawanda]],<ref>{{cite news | last=WIVB Staff | url=https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/niagara-county/north-tonawanda/a-quiet-place-2-looking-to-film-in-north-tonawanda/ | title='A Quiet Place 2' looking to film in North Tonawanda | work=[[WIVB-TV]] | date=August 2, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219212831/https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/niagara-county/north-tonawanda/a-quiet-place-2-looking-to-film-in-north-tonawanda/ | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> and Barcelona Harbor in the town of [[Westfield, New York|Westfield]] in [[Chautauqua County, New York|Chautauqua County]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Tichy | first=Eric | url=https://www.observertoday.com/news/page-one/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-lands-at-barcelona/ | title='A Quiet Place 2' lands at Barcelona | work=Observer Today | publisher=[[Ogden Newspapers]] | date=August 9, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810135958/https://www.observertoday.com/news/page-one/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-lands-at-barcelona/ | archive-date=August 10, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Filming also took place on a [[sound stage]] in Buffalo. One of the last filming locations, the northbound [[South Grand Island Bridge]], was shut down for 13 hours for filming.<ref>{{cite news | last=Besecker | first=Aaron | url=https://buffalonews.com/2019/08/19/a-quiet-place-2-filming-to-close-grand-island-bridge-for-13-hours/ | title='A Quiet Place 2' filming to close Grand Island bridge for 13 hours | work=[[The Buffalo News]] | date=August 19, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915160236/https://buffalonews.com/2019/08/19/a-quiet-place-2-filming-to-close-grand-island-bridge-for-13-hours/ | archive-date=September 15, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Western New York, filming took place in the NY region of [[Hudson Valley]], specifically the towns of [[Dover, New York|Dover]], [[Pawling (town), New York|Pawling]], and [[New Paltz, New York|New Paltz]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Barry | first=John W. | url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/2020/04/03/coronavirus-a-quiet-place-part-ii-john-krasinski-emily-blunt-paramount-pictures/2938691001/ | title=Coronavirus: 'A Quiet Place Part II' now set for Sept. 4 release in theaters | work=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]] | date=April 3, 2020 | accessdate=April 3, 2020 }}\n*{{cite news | last=Barry | first=John W. | url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2019/09/13/john-krasinskis-a-quiet-place-sequel-close-road-production/2309956001/ | title=John Krasinski's 'A Quiet Place' sequel to close road for production | work=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]] | date=September 13, 2019 | accessdate=April 3, 2020 }}</ref> In New Paltz, the [[Wallkill Valley Rail Trail]] was revisited to film on a bridge that featured in the first film.<ref>{{cite news | last=Wilson | first=Geoffrey | url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/entertainment/movies/2019/09/19/a-quiet-place-sequel-film-crew-returns-new-paltz-bridge/2375770001/ | title='A Quiet Place' sequel: Film crew returns to New Paltz bridge featured in original movie | work=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]] | date=September 19, 2019 | accessdate=April 3, 2020 }}</ref> The production invested over $10 million in [[Upstate New York]], created 400 hires, and involved 300 background actors.<ref>{{cite news | last=Herbert | first=Geoff | url=https://www.newyorkupstate.com/entertainment/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-continues-filming-in-western-ny-marvel-star-joins-cast.html | title='A Quiet Place 2' continues filming in Western NY; Marvel star joins cast | work=[[The Post-Standard]] | date=August 14, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814153334/https://www.newyorkupstate.com/entertainment/2019/08/a-quiet-place-2-continues-filming-in-western-ny-marvel-star-joins-cast.html | archive-date=August 14, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> By late September, production was finished.<ref>{{cite news | last=Hermanns | first=Grant | url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1101485-a-quiet-place-part-ii-wraps-production | title=A Quiet Place Part II Wraps Production! | work=[[ComingSoon.net]] | date=September 25, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Sound design===\nFor the sequel's sound design, supervising sound editors [[Erik Aadahl]] and [[Ethan Van der Ryn]] and [[re-recording mixer]] [[Brandon Proctor]] reprised their roles. Krasinski instructed them to try to \"follow the rules\" set up in the first film and said of the experience, \"What we found was by doing that, and not trying to be cool, we ended up uncovering way more stuff than we ever would've been able to [otherwise].\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Oller | first=Jacob | url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/quiet-place-part-ii-sound-design-follow-the-rules | title=John Krasinski's one rule for A Quiet Place Part II's sound design: 'Just follow the rules' | work=[[Syfy Wire]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 10, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n\nParamount Pictures previewed a 30-second teaser trailer for ''A Quiet Place Part II'' before select theatrical screenings of ''[[Black Christmas (2019 film)|Black Christmas]]'', which was released on December 13, 2019. Less than a week later, the teaser trailer became available online. A full trailer was released on January 1, 2020.<ref name=\"evans20191218\" /> During pre-game coverage before the [[Super Bowl LIV]] on February 2, 2020, Paramount released a 30-second TV spot,<ref name=\"evans20200131\" /> which revealed that Krasinski reprised his role in a newly-filmed flashback sequence.<ref>{{cite news | last=Chitwood | first=Adam | url=https://collider.com/a-quiet-place-2-super-bowl-2020-ad-trailer/ | title='A Quiet Place: Part II' Super Bowl Ad Has a Big Surprise | work=[[Collider.com]] | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201131147/https://collider.com/a-quiet-place-2-super-bowl-2020-ad-trailer/ | archive-date=February 1, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March, Paramount initiated \"survival room\" experiences in New York and Los Angeles in which groups of visitors can try to overcome \"physical and mental obstacles\" without making too much noise.<ref>{{cite news | last=Rosenberg | first=Adam | url=https://mashable.com/article/quiet-place-2-survival-rooms-poster-trailer/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Survival Rooms invite fans to live the horror for themselves | work=[[Mashable]] | date=February 25, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 }}</ref> The setups cost less than a million dollars for Paramount. A marketing executive anticipated between seven thousand and eight thousand people to go through the experiences and for fans and [[social media influencer]]s to engage in [[experiential marketing]].<ref>{{cite magazine | last=Handy | first=Bruce | url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/16/shhhhh-choosing-to-be-very-afraid | title=Shhh! Choosing to Be Very Afraid | magazine=[[The New Yorker]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 9, 2020 }}</ref> [[Emily Blunt]] appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' on March 10 to promote the film. She appeared in a parody commercial advertising ''A Quiet Plane'', starring as a stewardess that enforces silence as a top priority to a plane's passengers.<ref>{{cite news | last=Jackson | first=Matthew | url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/emily-blunt-a-quiet-place-part-ii-spoof | title=Emily Blunt creates world's quietest airline in A Quiet Place late night spoof | work=[[Syfy Wire]] | date=March 11, 2020 | accessdate=March 11, 2020 }}</ref> Before the film's postponement ([[#Release|see below]]), Paramount planned to host a [[double feature|double-feature]] event that screened the first and second films with collectors prints provided to attendees.<ref>{{cite news | last=Perez | first=Chris | url=https://www.cbr.com/paramount-a-quiet-place-parts-i-ii-event/ | title=Paramount Announces A Quiet Place Parts I and II Double Feature Event | work=[[Comic Book Resources]] | date=February 29, 2020 | accessdate=March 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Box office forecast==\nIn January 2020, ''[[BoxOffice (magazine)|BoxOffice]]'' predicted the film would gross {{nowrap|$72 million}} in its initially-announced opening weekend in late March 2020. (The film was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].) It based the forecast on the first film's success on its own opening weekend ({{nowrap|$50.2 million}}) and in the long run, the sequel's early social metrics being strong, and the continued involvement of Emily Blunt and John Krasinski. The site also noted that the film would face competition from the likes of ''[[Mulan (2020 film)|Mulan]]''.<ref>{{cite news | last=Robbins | first=Shawn | url=https://www.boxofficepro.com/long-range-box-office-tracking-a-quiet-place-part-ii/ | title=Long Range Box Office Tracking: ''A Quiet Place Part II'' | work=[[BoxOffice (magazine)|BoxOffice]] | date=January 24, 2020 | accessdate=January 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127141420/https://www.boxofficepro.com/long-range-box-office-tracking-a-quiet-place-part-ii/ | archive-date=January 27, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"pallotta\" /> In February, early industry tracking had the film debuting to around $55-60 million.<ref name=\"d'alessandro\" /><ref>{{cite magazine | last=Rubin | first=Rebecca | url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/box-office-a-quiet-place-2-early-tracking-1203517739/ | title=Box Office: 'A Quiet Place 2' Tracking for $55 Million-Plus Debut | magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 28, 2020 }}</ref> Analysts compared the debut to those of recent films ''[[Us (2019 film)|Us]]'', ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'', ''[[Halloween (2018 film)|Halloween]]'', and ''[[It Chapter Two]]''. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]''{{'}}s Anthony D'Alessandro wrote, \"''A Quiet Place Part II'' is currently strong with females under 25, African Americans and Hispanic demos, but overall I hear it's strong with all quads.\"<ref name=\"d'alessandro\">{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url= https://deadline.com/2020/02/a-quiet-place-part-ii-to-scare-up-60m-opening-early-box-office-forecast-1202869747/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' To Scare Up $60M Opening&nbsp;\u2013 Early Box Office Forecast | date=February 27, 2020 | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n''A Quiet Place Part II'' had its world premiere at the [[Lincoln Center]] in [[New York City]] on {{nowrap|March 8}}, 2020.<ref>{{cite news | last=Martin | first=Annie | url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/Movies/2020/03/09/John-Krasinski-praises-Emily-Blunt-at-A-Quiet-Place-2-premiere/6121583758813/ | title=John Krasinski praises Emily Blunt at 'A Quiet Place 2' premiere | work=[[United Press International]] | date=March 9, 2020 | accessdate=March 9, 2020 }}</ref> [[Paramount Pictures]] plans to release the film in theaters on {{nowrap|September 4}}, 2020 after it postponed a March 2020 release due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite magazine | last=McClintock | first=Pamela | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/a-quiet-place-part-ii-sets-new-september-2020-release-date-1287096 | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Sets New September Release Date | magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=April 2, 2020 | accessdate=April 2, 2020 }}</ref> The September release date, announced on {{nowrap|April 2}}, is the start of the US holiday weekend [[Labor Day Weekend]]. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' wrote the weekend is \"summer [box office's] finale\" and \"typically the deadest period ever for moviegoing\" but that the studio anticipated pent-up demand after pandemic fears subside.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/top-gun-maverick-flies-to-christmas-corridor-spongebob-eyes-late-summer-quiet-place-ii-to-debut-labor-day-1202898738/ | title='Top Gun Maverick' Flies To Christmas Corridor, 'SpongeBob' Eyes Late Summer, 'Quiet Place II\u2019 To Debut Labor Day | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=April 2, 2020 | accessdate=April 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe studio initially planned to release the film in theaters globally starting on March 18, 2020 before it delayed the film's release due to the pandemic. Director John Krasinski said he wanted moviegoers to see the film together and that with the pandemic, it was not the right time to provide that experience.<ref name=\"grater\">{{cite news | last=Grater | first=Tom | url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/a-quiet-place-ii-delayed-coronavirus-crisis-1202880784/ | title='A Quiet Place II' Global Release Delayed To Avoid Coronavirus Crisis&nbsp;\u2013 Update | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=March 12, 2020 | accessdate=March 12, 2020 }}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' said that according to sources, Paramount spent around 60% of its budget for global prints and advertising. The periodical wrote that the film's delay was \"truly a shocker\" because the P&A expense seemed to indicate that rescheduling was not an option.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/mulan-new-mutants-antlers-moved-coronavirus-1202881355/ | title='Mulan', 'New Mutants' & 'Antlers' Moved By Disney As Coronavirus Grips Release Schedule | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=March 12, 2020 | accessdate=March 13, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe film was initially to be released in the United Kingdom and Australia on March 19, 2020,<ref>{{cite news | last=Bisset | first=Jennifer | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/a-quiet-place-2-first-reactions-slink-in/ | title=A Quiet Place 2 first reactions slink in: 'A masterclass in suspense' | work=[[CNET]] | date=March 5, 2020 | accessdate=March 6, 2020 }}</ref> and in the United States and Canada, including [[Dolby Cinema]] and [[IMAX]], on March 20, 2020.<ref name=\"evans20191218\">{{cite news | last=Evans | first=Greg | url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/a-quiet-place-part-ii-teaser-poster-release-emily-blunt-john-krasinski-1202812560/ | title='A Quiet Place Part II' Teaser Finally Making Noise Outside Sneak Peek Screenings | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=December 18, 2019 | accessdate=December 18, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218152102/https://deadline.com/2019/12/a-quiet-place-part-ii-teaser-poster-release-emily-blunt-john-krasinski-1202812560/ | archive-date=December 18, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Paramount initially stated on March 6 that it would not reschedule the film in response to the pandemic,<ref name=\"pallotta\">{{cite news | last=Pallotta | first=Frank | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/media/coronavirus-james-bond-box-office/index.html | title='No Time to Die' was the first major film to delay its release due to coronavirus. It may not be the last | work=[[CNN]] | date=March 6, 2020 | accessdate=March 9, 2020 }}</ref> but on March 12, the studio pulled the film from release worldwide with the intent of scheduling it later in the year.<ref name=\"grater\" /> Almost a year earlier, the film had initially been scheduled to be released on May 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite news | last=D'Alessandro | first=Anthony | url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/a-quiet-place-2-sonic-the-hedgehog-playing-with-fire-paramount-release-dates-1202622152/ | title='A Quiet Place 2' Going Earlier In 2020, 'Playing With Fire' Takes Over 'Sonic'{{'}}s November Spot: Paramount Release Date Changes | work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=May 24, 2019 | accessdate=October 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527020114/https://deadline.com/2019/05/a-quiet-place-2-sonic-the-hedgehog-playing-with-fire-paramount-release-dates-1202622152/ | archive-date=May 27, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nProducer [[Brad Fuller (producer)|Brad Fuller]] said for the film's US release, Paramount sought to maintain a [[PG-13]] rating (parental guidance suggested) like its predecessor and to avoid an R rating (restricted audiences) to appeal to a broad audience, including those who are offput by blood in R-rated horror films.<ref>{{cite news | last=Mobley | first=Joshua | url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/a-quiet-place-part-2-how-they-kept-the-gimmick-sca/1100-6474288/ | title=A Quiet Place Part 2: How They Kept The Gimmick Scary For The Sequel | work=[[GameSpot]] | date=March 11, 2020 | accessdate=March 11, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n*[[List of films featuring the deaf and hard of hearing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.aquietplacemovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt8332922}}\n\n{{Films directed by John Krasinski}}\n{{Platinum Dunes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quiet Place Part II, A}}\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:2020s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American monster movies]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American Sign Language films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about deaf people]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Krasinski]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Andrew Form]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Bradley Fuller]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael Bay]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Platinum Dunes films]]\n[[Category:Sequel films]]\n", "name_user": "OromoDay", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelease:added a bullet point on 'see also'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Quiet_Place_Part_II"}
